<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0026EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CapitalGains Bjt   09-30 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Gains, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Balking at Bush's Capital Gains Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's capital gains tax cut, which
won a bitter fight in the House, may face trouble in the Senate
because of concerns that it is ill-timed and gives too large a tax
savings to the nation's richest people.
   The Senate has traditionally leaned strongly toward such
reductions, but some senators who have favored capital gains cuts
in the past find the new proposal unacceptable because of the
current budget deficit and its tilt to the wealthy.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee and
longtime backer of lower taxes on capital gains, said he will
recommend that a capital gains cut not be included when the
committee begins work Monday on a deficit-reduction plan.
   Bentsen, D-Texas, said Friday that an incentive for saving and
investment is needed, but a temporary cut followed by an increased
rate ``would destabilize the markets. It's sheer budget gimmickry.''
   Instead, Bentsen is proposing that tax-deductible Individual
Retirement Accounts be made available to more workers to encourage
saving.
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., a member of the committee, said the
panel is likely to reject the capital gains reduction and accept
the IRA alternative.
   Senate Majority Leader George J. Mitchell, D-Maine, said ``I
think there is a reasonably good chance we'll be able to prevail''
in the Senate and defeat the capital gains cut.
   If that happened, tax-writers from the House and Senate would
have to negotiate some kind of compromise that could include both a
capital gains reduction and liberalized IRAs.
   In a hard-fought vote Thursday, the House accepted a plan
supported by Bush that would reduce capital gains tax rates for 27
months. The maximum rate, now 33 percent, would be cut to 20
percent. On Jan. 1, 1992, the top rate would be raised to 28
percent and investments ``indexed'' so that profits caused by
inflation would not be taxed.
   There is general agreement that cutting the rates would
encourage investors to sell assets before the rates rose again,
generating about $9.4 billion in new revenue over three years.
Bentsen insists ``this yo-yo effect'' would do nothing to encourage
long-term investment.
   But the strongest political point about the capital gains cut is
that by any reckoning, most of the tax saving would go to those
with the greatest wealth.
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., said the reduction would
simply be ``mailing a check for $25,000 to every Republican
contributor in the last campaign.''
   The Joint Committee on Taxation estimates that people with
incomes above $200,000 who report capital gains would get tax cuts
averaging $24,906 apiece.
   ``It is hard for me to understand why this whole discussion has
to reach the level of rich versus poor,'' Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady told a Senate Finance Committee hearing Friday.
   ``The rich are getting richer in this country and the poor are
getting poorer,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D. ``You'll have to
forgive us for bringing it up.''
   The joint-committee staff, which provides tax expertise to the
House and Senate, estimates 80 percent of the tax saving from the
capital gains cut would go to couples and individuals with incomes
above $100,000 a year.
   Brady contends that figure is misleading because the
over-$100,000 category includes many people of relatively modest
earnings who, once in a lifetime, sell a small business or a home
and show greater incomes in that one year.
   The secretary estimated that 47 percent of capital gains are
realized by people whose other income _ not including the gains _
is less than $50,000 a year.
   But Bentsen said the joint-committee staff found that only 18
percent of the gains were taken by people who reported just one
capital gains transaction _ including sale of a home or business _
a year.
   Brady also said more than 80 percent of the tax saving from the
IRA expansion proposed by Bentsen would go to workers with incomes
above $50,000 a year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
