<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0057EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmPrices     09-30 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Prices,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA: Farmers Selling Products for Less</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average prices farmers receive for their
raw products are continuing to decline from last year's record
heights, the Agriculture Department says.
   The department's price index hit an 11-month low in September,
falling 0.7 percent from August to leave the monthly average also
0.7 percent below the level a year ago, the USDA said in
preliminary figures released Friday.
   Lower prices for cattle, hogs and potatoes were mostly
responsible for the decrease from the August average, the
department's Agricultural Statistics Board said in its report.
   Higher prices for oranges, milk, lettuce and applies partly
offset the decline for the other commodities during the month.
   ``Compared with a year earlier, lower prices for soybeans, corn,
tomatoes and oats more than offset higher prices for milk, cotton,
potatoes and eggs,'' the report said.
   Milk prices gained for the fourth consecutive month, winding up
in September at the highest level since February 1985.
   ``Feed grain prices were mixed, but corn, the major component of
this index, increased three cents (per bushel) from August,'' the
report said. ``An 18-cent (per bushel) decrease in the price of
soybeans moved the oil-bearing crop index lower.''
   No change was reported in the prices farmers pay to meet
expenses. Those are adjusted every three months, and the next will
be reported in October. The July ``prices paid'' index was up 0.6
percent from April and 3.5 percent from July 1988.
   Department economists say net cash income of farmers _ gross
cash income minus cash expenses _ is expected to decline 5 percent
to 13 percent from last year's record of $59.9 billion.
   The 1988 drought forced commodity prices up, and many producers
were able to sell harvests at the higher prices, thus more than
offsetting reduced production. Also, many farmers had grain stored
from previous crops and were able to cash in as prices rose.
   Economists say the cash income decline this year is expected to
stem from farmers' larger cash expenses as they boost plantings,
and also because of lower federal subsidies.
   Consumer food prices are forecast by USDA to rise an average of
5 percent to 7 percent this year, following a 4.1 percent increase
in 1988.
   Based on the preliminary figures, the September price index for
livestock and livestock products as a group decreased 1.9 percent
from August but averaged 3.3 percent above the year-earlier level.
   Crop prices, overall, rose 0.8 percent from August but averaged
5.9 percent less than in September 1988.
   The all-fruit price index for September was up 22 percent from
August and was 6.4 percent above a year ago, the report said.
Rising prices for oranges had the greatest impact on the index,
followed by apples, peaches, strawberries, lemons and grapefruit.
   Prices of commercial vegetables dropped 10 percent from August,
averaging 16 percent below a year ago, the report said.
   The overall index of prices paid to farmers in September
averaged 143 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison, down from
144 percent in August. That was the lowest for the index since
October 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
