<DOCNO> AP890930-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0446EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--CrackHouse     09-30 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Crack House,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Gets Probation for Torching Trailer She Believed Was Crack
House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said she was inspired by President
Bush's anti-drug speech received two years probation for setting
fire to a vacant trailer she believed was a crack house, a
prosecutor said.
   Jessie Mell Gross, 54, was sentenced to two years deferred
adjudication in connection with the Monday fire that destroyed the
trailer, prosecutor Kathy Braddock said Friday.
   Judge Jimmy James declined to fine Ms. Gross a $500 fine
requested by the prosecutor, Braddock said.
   Police had responded several times to complaints about fights
and disturbances at the trailer park, but only Ms. Gross complained
about alleged drug use at the vacant trailer, Ms. Braddock said.
Police weren't able to determine if the trailer was used as a crack
house.
   Ms. Braddock said that Ms. Gross told authorities she was
inspired to do something to stop drug use after watching Bush's
speech earlier this month.
</TEXT>
