<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-four junior high school students in
Spanish Harlem received a promise from talk show host Geraldo
Rivera: Stay in school, and he'll pick up the tab for college.
   Rivera said Friday that he made the promise to a ninth-grade
class at Junior High School 45 ``to put them on a better course
than their buddies might have in the same neighborhood.''
   Rivera befriended the students last year through the Board of
Education's Adopt-A-Class program, in which companies and
individuals monitor and encourage students' development.
   He has provided book and clothing allowances so far, but admits
that sending the students to college ``could get pretty pricey,
especially if one of them goes to Harvard.''
   ``I feel one person can make a difference in the choices people
make,'' said Rivera, host of the syndicated show, ``Geraldo.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor David Carradine, perhaps best known as
the Buddhist monk in the hit 1970s television series ``Kung Fu,''
pleaded no contest to drunken driving, officials said.
   Municipal Court Commissioner David Stephens on Friday sentenced
Carradine, 52, to three years' summary probation, a 48-hour jail
term, 100 hours of community service and 30 days' work for the
California Department of Transportation, city attorney's spokesman
Ted Goldstein said.
   In addition, Carradine must attend a drunken driving awareness
meeting and complete a one-year alcohol rehabilitation program.
   Stephens imposed the harsh sentence because Carradine is a
second-time offender, Goldstein said.
   Carradine was arrested Sept. 8 after an officer noticed him
stopping repeatedly at green traffic lights, Goldstein said.
