<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-FEMA Bjt   09-30 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-FEMA, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storm-Weary Residents Angry Over Slow Federal Response</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shannon Chevrier hoped to get federal
aid to help cover the losses she suffered from Hurricane Hugo, but
instead she got a packet full of paperwork and was told it might be
two months before she saw any money.
   ``I expected something a little bit quicker,'' Miss Chevrier,
24, said Friday after visiting a Federal Emergency Management
Agency center set up to help hurricane victims.
   ``We don't need help two months from now. We need it right
away,'' she said. ``I'm out of work, I'm out of money. I'm angry.''
   The Charleston woman, one of hundreds of people who sought help
at one of five emergency centers, has not worked since the
hurricane hit Sept. 21. The bookkeeping firm that employs her has
been closed because the city is largely without power.
   She called the government response ``too little, too late. I
would expect in something like this the federal government would
respond quicker.''
   President Bush toured the storm-damaged areas for two hours
Friday, and acknowledged afterward that ``there's been a critic or
two'' of the federal relief effort. ``To the critics, I simply say:
I understand. We are trying very hard,'' he said.
   FEMA set up the centers to help residents apply for cash grants,
low-interest loans and jobless benefits. They can also seek answers
to questions about insurance claims, how to claim losses on tax
forms and register complaints about gouging.
   But for many, cutting through a tangle of government red tape is
just the latest hardship spawned by the storm that crashed into
Charleston with 135 mph winds.
   There have been complaints that there are too few centers and
that the process is too slow. The first centers did not open until
Thursday _ a full week after the storm hit.
   ``I thought they were kidding about the paperwork. It's
ridiculous,'' said Genie VanBenschoten, 26, holding a packet of
forms she needed to fill out and return.
   Those who came to one center Friday were given applications and
scheduled for an appointment. Some will not be seen until Oct. 10.
   ``Most of these people have lost everything. I feel for them but
this process is necessary,'' FEMA manager Shirley Caraway said.
   FEMA can provide loans of up to $100,000 to repair or replace
homes; up to $20,000 to replace personal property and up to
$500,000 for businesses.
   Also available are funds for temporary housing, rental
assistance and individual and family grants for needs not covered
by insurance.
   FEMA said 2,071 people had applied for federal aid at five
disaster relief centers in Charleston, Mount Pleasant, Sumter,
Myrtle Beach and Georgetown by Friday afternoon. Another 5,710 made
appointments to return next week.
   Five more centers were scheduled to open over the weekend in
Lancaster, Manning, Camden, Kingstree and Monck's Corner.
   Ron Ruffennach, a FEMA spokesman, said individuals' income is
used to determine whether they are awarded grants or low-interest
loans.
   One FEMA center is handling about 60 people every two hours and
officials said that by today they would handle 90 people within two
hours.
   Those who need immediate help are referred to the Red Cross or
Salvation Army, which have representatives at the center. The Red
Cross can issue vouchers for food, clothing, shelter, towels, soap
or other necessities.
   Some people expected immediate help from the government, but
FEMA officials said claims must be processed and verified before
taxpayers dollars are released.
   People filing emergency unemployment claims may wait for two to
three weeks. Officials would not say how long it might take for
small business loans to be forthcoming.
   ``You don't come in today and get a check tomorrow,'' said Jean
King, of the South Carolina Employment Security Commission.
   ``Rumors and misinformation have been rampant,'' said Kathryn
Kidd of the University of South Carolina Sociology Department, who
was assisting FEMA.
   Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. was an early critic of the
federal response.
   ``We really need more disaster assistance centers,'' Riley said.
``They were slow getting started, and I think that shows maybe some
weakness in the system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
