<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     09-30 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Expect Complete Halt In Aid From Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   El Salvador's leftist guerrillas expect a
complete halt in aid from Nicaragua after last month's Central
American peace accords, but say they will maintain themselves as a
fighting force anyway.
   ``We expect the Nicaraguans to comply with the peace accords not
100 percent, but 101 percent,'' Miguel Saenz, of the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front's political-military commission
said in an interview Friday.
   Nicaragua's President Daniel Ortega and the four other Central
American presidents signed a peace accord on Aug. 7 in which they
agreed that no irregular forces would be allowed to operate from
their territories.
   The accord also called for disbanding Nicaragua's U.S.-supported
Contra rebels in exchange for democratic elections and other
reforms inside Nicaragua.
   ``The Sandinistas have to abide by the accords they've signed.
They have a lot to gain,'' Saenz said.
   Saenz and Salvador Samayoa, another Front official, also said
they expected Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani to offer an
immediate, unconditional cease-fire when he speaks to the United
Nations General Assembly on Monday.
   They said a cease-fire in El Salvador was impossible without
agreement on measures to advance democracy and protect leftist
activists.
   ``If there are no guarantees, a cease-fire is a fiction,'' said
Salvador Samayoa, a member of the Front's political-diplomatic
commission. ``They will keep imprisoning our activists, there will
still be violence. It's all a kind of show.''
   The two officials said peace talks earlier this month in Mexico
City went well, and that they were optimistic about a second
session on Oct. 16 to 17 in Costa Rica, even though they felt
Cristiani's rightist government is stalling.
   ``They really believe we depend on the Nicaraguans,'' said
Samayoa. ``They figure if they stall the talks, time is on their
side, we'll get weaker and they'll win.''
   ``If they stick to that, we will have to show that their
analysis is wrong through more confrontation,'' Samayoa said. The
two officials noted that the Front launched an offensive this week
that has affected 10 of the nation's 14 provinces.
   Salvadoran guerrilla sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, have said there are 150,000 weapons available for
purchase in Central America, and that the guerrillas have the
resources to buy them.
   Among the sellers, these sources say, are the gradually
disbanding Contra guerrillas who have been fighting the Sandinista
government in Nicaragua since 1981.
   Samayoa said that even if the Front cannot win El Salvador's
10-year-old civil war militarily, that does not mean a victory for
the government.
   ``Supposing we can't win, we can guarantee they won't be able to
carry out their programs,'' said Samayoa. ``It's not just a
question of winning, but a question of governing and of
reactivating the economy.''
   The war in El Salvador has taken more than 70,000 lives and
wrecked the economy in the nation of 5 million, despite a total of
$3.8 billion in U.S. economic and military aid.
   In a peace proposal made in Mexico City, the rebels demanded
judicial reforms, an end to repression, maintenance of economic,
especially land, reforms made since 1980 and a cleansing and
shrinking of the army.
   They also asked for democratic constitutional reforms and
clearly defined cease-fire lines. In a notable change from previous
proposals, the guerrillas did not demand a power-sharing
arrangement in advance of a settlement.
</TEXT>
