<FIRST>r a PM-OperationRescue     09-30 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Operation Rescue,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Operation Rescue Leader Convicted on Charges Stemming From Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury convicted the leader of the Operation
Rescue anti-abortion group of charges resulting from a protest at a
health clinic during last year's Democratic National Convention.
   Randall Terry was convicted Friday of criminal trespass and
unlawful assembly charges.
   The state then asked Judge John Bruner to impose the maximum
sentence of 12 months in prison and a fine of $1,000 for each of
the two counts. At Terry's request, though, the judge postponed
sentencing until Thursday.
   Terry, who remained free on a personal recognizance bond, told
reporters that the trial had ``been a classic example of a
miscarriage of justice ... a kangaroo court.''
   ``How could I expect justice in a court that protects
murderers?'' he added, a reference to repeated rulings from the
judge that abortion was not on trial.
   Chief Assistant Solicitor Robert Lee O'Brien, who prosecuted the
case, told Bruner after the verdict that Terry's conduct throughout
the trial led the state to believe ``he will continue engaging in
unlawful activities of this nature.''
   He urged the judge to impose the maximum combination of jail
time and fines, but said that if he intended to waive a jail
sentence, the judge should order that the fines collected before
allowing Terry to leave the court's jurisdiction.
   Terry appealed for a delay before sentencing ``to allow me time
to get my house in order.'' He promised to return, saying, ``I'm a
national leader. There's no place to run. I wouldn't want to run
anyway. It would be a disgrace to the cause.''
   In closing arguments, Terry _ who represented himself without a
lawyer _ said he was a would-be rescuer of unborn children. O'Brien
called him a man intent on pressing his own moral values on others.
   Terry is among 60 anti-abortion demonstrators on the trial in
Fulton County State Court, but only a handful are expected to be
tried in the next few weeks.
   More than 1,200 arrests were made during at least 20 protests at
various abortion clinics organized by Operation Rescue during the
summer and fall of 1988.
</TEXT>
