<FIRST>u i PM-Israel     09-30 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Frees Soldiers Convicted of Beating Palestinian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three soldiers convicted in the beating of a
Palestinian were released early in a case viewed as a test of the
army's commitment to punishing troops who use brutality against the
Arab uprising.
   The Palestinian, Hani El-Shami, later died in a second beating
by other soldiers, a military court said. His case has been one of
the most contentious and publicized in the 21-month-old Palestinian
revolt against Israeli rule of the occupied lands.
   The government announced the pardon on Friday, just hours before
the start of Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year. The soldiers, who
were sentenced to nine months for brutality, had three more months
to serve.
   Israeli liberals warned that releasing the three men could
encourage further abuse by soldiers faced with the task of putting
down the revolt.
   ``It's a sign to other soldiers that this act is not really so
bad,'' Yossi Sarid, a Parliament member from the leftist Citizens
Rights Movement Party, told Israel radio.
   Maj. Gen. Matal Vilnai, chief of the army's southern command,
cut the soldiers' sentences, resulting in their immediate release.
He barred them from returning to the elite Givati infantry brigade
in which they had served.
   ``The action is only a reduction of the actual prison time,'' an
army statement said. ``(Vilnai) does not erase the crime and the
conviction, which remain attributed to these soldiers.''
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who reportedly asked Vilnai to
cut the soldiers' sentences, told Israel radio that bad publicity
over the case had hurt army morale.
   The three men and a fourth soldier initially were charged with
manslaughter in the death of El-Shami, 42, who was beaten with
rifle butts and a broomstick at his home in the Gaza Strip's
Jabaliya refugee camp on Aug. 22, 1988.
   They were found innocent of the charge in May by a military
court, which ruled El-Shami died after a later beating by other
soldiers. The defendants were convicted of brutality, and no
charges have been brought against any other soldiers in the case.
   The fourth defendant was freed earlier after completing his
six-month sentence.
   The soldiers contended they were following orders.
   Also Friday, Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said in a newspaper
interview that ``Israel can live with the intefadeh,'' the Arabic
word for the uprising that began in December 1987.
   Shamir told the Davar daily the government has not used all its
means to crush the revolt.
   ``If Israel is always convinced that it cannot compromise or
give in to these demands, it will continue to stand in this fight
and it can continue for a long time. We are stronger, they are the
sufferers,'' he said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, Shefta Khalil Abu Tarr, 70, was
beaten to death in the town of Khan Yunis by fellow Arabs who
accused him of collaborating with Israeli authorities, Arab
reporters said.
   The killing brought to 122 the number of Arabs killed by other
Palestinians as suspected collaborators. Since the uprising began,
575 Arabs have been killed by Israeli soldiers or Jewish settlers
and 40 Israelis have been slain.
</TEXT>
