<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Busch     09-30 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Busch,0671</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beer Baron, Ballclub President August A. Busch Jr. Dead at 90</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ST1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   August A. Busch Jr., the beer baron and
baseball club president who was the city's best-known ambassador,
has died after a brief illness. He was 90.
   Busch died Friday at his home on Grant's Farm in suburban St.
Louis, according to a statement from his family.
   The patriarch of the world's largest brewing dynasty, Busch also
was remembered as St. Louis' biggest fan and a person who would
invite visitors into his home to have a beer and talk about his
team _ the St. Louis Cardinals. ``He was Mr. Anheuser-Busch, Mr.
Budweiser, Mr. Cardinal and he was Mr. St. Louis ... ,'' said Fred
Kuhlmann, chief operating officer of the Cardinals.
   Busch was hospitalized on Aug. 29 for routine tests and returned
home about two weeks ago. He had been suffering from pneumonia, but
his family declined to give the cause of death.
   Busch made Anheuser-Busch the brewing giant it is today, and he
built the Cardinals into one of baseball's most successful teams.
   At the time of his death, he was the honorary chairman of the
board of Anheuser-Busch, president and chief executive officer of
the Cardinals and a civic leader.
   At the start of each baseball season, Busch would ride atop the
Budweiser beer wagon around Busch Stadium by eight massive
Clydesdale horses.
   As the wagon emerged from the Cards bullpen with Gussie, as
Busch was called, waving a red cowboy hat, the organist would play
the Budweiser anthem, ``Here Comes the King.''
   ``We mourn his death while celebrating his many
accomplishments,'' baseball commissionier Fay Vincent said.
   In 1953, Busch convinced the company's board of directors that
it should purchase the team and renovate old Sportsmans Park.
   Later, when developers ran out of money for the new Busch
Stadium in downtown St. Louis, Busch helped raise the additional $3
million needed. The company now owns the stadium.
   ``He was clearly one of the legendary leaders of St. Louis,''
said Mayor Vincent C. Schoemehl Jr. ``His vision and his drive that
resulted in bringing Busch Stadium into downtown St. Louis formed
the basis for three decades of growth in downtown St. Louis. He
will be sorely missed.''
   Busch took a small, ailing brewery in 1946 and turned it into
the world's largest by the time he retired in 1975.
   The brewery grew under his direction from producing three
million barrels of beer annually to a record 37 million barrels at
the time of his retirement. Last year, it produced 78.5 million
barrels, 38 million more than its nearest competitor.
   In 1922, he went to work for his father, August Anheuser Busch
Sr., cleaning vats and sweeping floors at the south-side brewery
started by his grandfather, Adolphus A. Busch, and Eberhard
Anheuser.
   Two years later, Busch was named general superintendent of
brewing operations just in time to face one of the company's
greatest crises _ Prohibition.
   Busch, his father and elder brother, Adolphus Busch III, kept
the company in operation despite the fact that its chief product
had been proclaimed illegal.
   The company diversified into other areas, producing yeast, corn
and salt syrup, refrigeration cabinets, soft drinks and car and
truck bodies.
   With the death of August A. Busch Sr. in 1934, control of the
company passed to his two sons. Adolphus Busch III died of cancer
in 1946 and Busch became president of the corporation.
   In 1957, Anheuser-Busch took first place among America's
brewers, a position it has held since.
   Busch, who was married four times, is survived by 10 children,
including August Busch III, current Anheuser-Busch chairman; a
sister; 27 grandchildren; nine great grandchildren; three nieces;
and two nephews.
   His fourth wife, Margaret Rohde Busch, died last year.
   Funeral services will be private and memorial arrangements are
pending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
