<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0432 09-30 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Thornburgh Can't Challenge Secrecy Rulings</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS lead to clarify.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh will have to
take action to drop criminal charges against an Iran-Contra figure
if he wants to protect secrets from being disclosed at the man's
trial, according to an appeals court ruling.
   A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Richmond, Va., on Friday rebuffed Thornburgh and said he could not
otherwise intervene to challenge secrecy rulings in the case
against Joseph F. Fernandez, a former CIA agent.
   The appeals court held that only independent counsel Lawrence E.
Walsh could appeal rulings allowing the disclosure of government
secrets in the trial.
   The court said Thornburgh's only recourse to protect the secrets
would be to exercise a politically unpalatable option the attorney
general had sought to avoid _ filing a motion that could lead to
the dismissal of charges.
   Thornburgh had sought to intervene to prevent the disclosure of
the location of CIA facilities in Central America that the trial
judge held could be made public as part of Fernandez's defense.
   The appellate panel said Thornburgh can still file an affidavit
blocking the release of the documents in open court, a move that
could force dismissal of the charges against Fernandez by U.S.
District Judge Claude Hilton of Alexandria, Va.
   The appellate court agreed with Walsh's contention that allowing
the attorney general to appeal secrecy rulings in the case would
undermine the independent counsel's ability to prosecute the case.
   ``We are, of course, gratified by their decision, and we will
proceed with the case,'' Walsh said in a statement.
   Thornburgh's spokesman, David Runkel, said, ``We're reviewing
the various options which the department has at this time.''
   Those options include seeking a rehearing of the case by the 4th
Circuit or appealing the ruling to the Supreme Court, Runkel said.
In addition, ``There is the option of discussing this with the
independent counsel to see if he could resolve the issue there,''
he said.
   Fernandez, who headed the CIA's station in San Jose, Costa Rica,
is accused of lying to agency superiors and a presidential
commission that investigated the Iran-Contra affair about his role
in helping North set up a covert arms supply network for the
Nicaraguan Contras.
</TEXT>
