<FIRST>r a PM-WanderingPlane     09-30 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds Find No Evidence `Mystery Pilot' Involved In Drug, Gun Running</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal drug investigators found no
evidence that pilot Thomas Root was involved in drug smuggling or
gun running when his plane crashed in the Atlantic Ocean after a
mysterious 800-mile flight, a newspaper reported today.
   ``In view of his explanations, no further investigative efforts
will be generated by our office,'' Mario Perez, spokesman for the
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration's Washington field office,
told the the Sun-Sentinel in Fort Lauderdale reported in today's
editions.
   Perez on Friday said the DEA, the supervising agency for the
federal drug enforcement task force, decided to close the
investigation after Root was interviewed by a DEA agent Sept. 21.
   The investigation began two days before Root set out on his
odyssey July 13 that ended when his plane, flying on autopilot, ran
out of fuel and crashed in the Atlantic Ocean near the Bahamas.
   ``All of his answers were plausible,'' Perez said.
   Root's wife, Kathy, reached at the family's Alexandria, Va.,
home Friday, expressed relief that her husband had been cleared of
wrongdoing in the federal drug probe.
   ``We're certainly glad that what his friends and family knew to
be true all along has been determined to be the case by the federal
government,'' she said.
   She said her husband has never used drugs.
   Root was not available for comment. He underwent a second
operation around midday Friday in connection with the mysterious
gunshot wound he suffered to the abdomen during the flight.
   Also Friday, a National Transportation Safety Board official
said that his agency had concluded its investigation into Root's
crash. But Jorge Prelezzo, NTSB regional director for Florida and
the Caribbean, could not say when a final report would be completed
and made public.
   Paul Miller, spokesman for the Miami field office of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation, said the FBI is continuing to pursue its
11-week-old probe into Root's activities in the days preceeding his
flight.
   The FBI inquiry began after doctors treating Root at Hollywood
Memorial Hospital following his rescue discovered he had been shot.
Root, 36, says he became ill and blacked out about an hour after
leaving Washington National Airport July 13, and does not know how
he suffered the gunshot wound.
   Two days before Root set out on his flight, the multi-agency
task force of federal, state and local law enforcement officials
discussed opening up an investigation on Root, based on a search
April 24 of his airplane hangar. That search resulted from a tip
that Root had stored a cache of drugs, guns and drug paraphernalia
in his hangar.
   But the search turned up no drugs, and all of the guns seized in
the search had federal or state licenses.
</TEXT>
