<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo     09-30 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Outlines Plan to Build Protective Line of Dunes Along Coast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo-FEMA, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CHT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina desperately needs to
build 65 miles of protective sand dunes in just over two weeks to
prevent further damage to a coastline already devastated by
Hurricane Hugo, Gov. Carroll Campbell said.
   ``If we don't do this now, I'm afraid we're going to forego the
coast,'' Campbell said Friday. ``It's mind-boggling, but we can do
it.''
   The state faces a race to beat a once-in-a-decade high tide that
begins in mid-October. The high tide is expected to cause more
beach erosion and further damage to already fragile structures
along the coast.
   Carroll and legislative leaders discussed the coastal plan after
President Bush brought sympathy and part of a $1.1 billion federal
aid package during a two-hour tour of storm-damaged areas.
   Bush bypassed Charleston and toured the suburb of Summerville by
car, seeing decimated trailer parks, dozens of roofless buildings
smashed cars pine forests mowed down by Hugo's winds. Later, he
rode a helicopter over the coastline and over some of the hardest
hit areas of downtown Charleston.
   The hurricane ``was tough. It was devastating,'' Bush told
reporters.
   ``But the spirit of the people of South Carolina came through
loud and clear,'' he said. ``You couldn't help but be impressed to
hear people say, `We're going to bounce back.'''
   The president acknowledged that many residents have criticized
the federal government's relief effort as too slow, but said, ``We
are trying very hard.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush directed the
Federal Emergency Management Agency to open four more
disaster-relief offices in Charleston. Mayor Joseph Riley had
criticized FEMA for having only two offices in the city.
   Of the $1.1 billion in Hugo-related emergency assistance Bush
signed shortly before arriving, $200 million will go to South
Carolina.
   The governor said he discussed the dune project with Bush.
Federal funds would cover three-fourths of the $65 million needed
for the project.
   From Oct. 14-17 and again from Nov. 12-15, daily high tides will
be more than 7 feet above the average low tide level, or 2 feet
higher than usual. That's because the moon is making its closest
approach to the Earth in years.
   ``The world thinks our coast is gone. That's what they see on
television. We've got to restore the beach and get it up for next
summer,'' Campbell said.
   If the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the South Carolina
Coastal Council say the project is feasible, ``We're going to
launch it right away,'' Campbell said. Much of the work could be
done by 2,000 members of two U.S. Army engineer battalions in South
Carolina, he added.
   The state Department of Corrections, meanwhile, turned down an
appeal from soul singer James Brown to be released from prison to
give a benefit concert to raise money for relief efforts,
corrections spokesman Francis X. Archibald said Friday.
   ``I simply want to do what I can to help restore these people's
lives, feed the hungry and house the homeless,'' Brown said in the
statement issued from the State Park Correctional Facility near
Columbia, S.C., where he is serving a six-year sentence for
aggravated assault and failing to stop for police.
   Offers of food and supplies continued to flood in from around
the country, meanwhile, and Charleston cut back its curfew by two
hours a day, leaving it in effect from 8 p.m. to 6 a.m.
   South Carolina Electric &amp; Gas Co. said 2,000 workers from 33
power companies in nine states were helping to restore power. But
nine days after the storm hit, about 200,000 residents remained
without power, about half of them in Charleston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
