<FIRST>r a PM-ZsaZsaTrial Bjt   09-30 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial, Bjt,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Convict Celebrity on 3 Misdemeanor Counts</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor, convicted of battery
for slapping a police officer and two other misdemeanor charges,
said her fame and outspoken self-defense led to the verdict _ which
she called ``ridiculous.''
   ``I know it's Zsa Zsa Gabor _ the diamonds. She loves to talk
up, she's not a milquetoast,'' said the actress, whose courtroom
outbursts and often outrageous out-of-court commentary on such
topics as police brutality and lesbianism had attracted news media
from around the world.
   The jury returned guilty verdicts Friday against Miss Gabor on
charges she slapped a motorcycle officer during a traffic stop and
was driving without a valid driver's license and with an open
container of alcohol in her car.
   The Hungarian-born star of such movies as ``Queen of Outer
Space'' and ``Picture Mommy Dead'' was acquitted on a fourth count
of disobeying Beverly Hills police Officer Paul Kramer as she drove
away while he was still checking her motor vehicle record on June
14.
   ``I can't believe in a country as great as ours that a 6-foot-4
policeman can beat up a lady of 5-foot-4, uses dirty language like
you were a streetwalker. ... I think Russia can't be worse than
this, or Communist Hungary either. I think it's ridiculous.''
   But juror Kevin Goodman, a 29-year-old Los Angeles attorney,
said, ``We felt a lot of weight as jurors in coming to the right
decision. We weren't in a deal-striking mood. There was no
compromise.''
   Municipal Court Judge Charles Rubin, who tried to limit
publicity by imposing what Miss Gabor called a ``gagging order,''
commended the jury for its work and hailed the trial as a model of
American justice.
   The trial was scheduled for one week, but took three.
   Miss Gabor, who claims to be 66 years old, faces up to 18 months
and five days in jail and a fine of $3,500. Sentencing was set for
Oct. 17.
   Rubin also fined Miss Gabor $500 for violating his gag order by
telling reporters that Kramer's fellow officer, Scott Thompson, had
lied on the witness stand while testifying for the prosecution.
   Thompson was called to buttress Kramer's account of the
incident, which began after he pulled Miss Gabor over for expired
registration tags on her white Rolls-Royce Corniche. As he checked
for other violations, she drove off.
   Miss Gabor admitted she slapped the officer after he stopped her
a second time. She said she reacted in self-defense when he pulled
her from her car, but he said the attack was unprovoked.
   The actress dismissed the possibility Friday that she would be
incarcerated.
   Prosecutor Eldon Fox also said he would not recommend the
actress be jailed. He said he would ask that Miss Gabor be ordered
to pay Los Angeles County for the cost of her trial, estimated at
$30,000.
   ``I want the $30,000 restitution to the court for this media
circus,'' he said.
   The star often arrived for the trial in the $215,000 Rolls that
had caused her so much trouble in the first place. On the first
day, she brought her hairdresser with her.
   At one point she told throngs of reporters her mother feared she
might be sent to jail, adding, ``Besides, they are all lesbians in
jail. And I'm so scared of lesbians. Can you imagine being in jail
with all those women?''
   She later apologized for the remark.
</TEXT>
