<FIRST>u i PM-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru a0449 09-30 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonn Seeks Easing of East German Refugee Situation At Embassies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with comment from Prague official; Minor
editing; No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was hope that 2,600 East Germans
confined to Bonn's embassy in Czechoslovakia might be allowed to
live in more tolerable conditions until they can flee to the West,
the government said.
   But there were no indications that they and 600 other East
German refugees waiting in Bonn's embassy in Warsaw, Poland would
be given permission to emigrate any time soon.
   ``The West German government, encouraged by the recent
expressions of the Prague government, expects at least a bearable
compromise in the humane interests of those involved,'' Klein said.
   He referred to prospects for alternative housing in Prague but
declined to give details, ``in order not to damage these very
difficult negotiations.''
   Since Sept. 10, more than 23,000 East Germans have fled to the
West through Hungary after that East bloc country opened its border
to Austria. West Germany offers automatic citizenship to East
Germans.
   But Czechoslovakia has said it will not allow the same kind of
mass migration westward. Poland has pressed the two Germanys to
work out a solution rather than following Hungary's action, which
has stirred conflict in the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   Polish Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski said Friday that
a solution to the refugee situation in Warsaw could come ``very
soon.''
   He talked to reporters after meeting with West German Foreign
Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher in New York, where both were
attending the U.N. General Assembly session.
   Health conditions have deteriorated at the embassy in Prague,
where refugees sleep three to a cot in tents jamming the muddy
compound. Many refugees, including hundreds of children, are
suffering from colds, flu and other weather-related illnesses.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Hanns Schumacher said no serious
infections were reported yet, but swift measures were needed.
   Klein said pictures of the embassy grounds appearing worldwide
testified to the ``human tragedy'' of thousands of East Germans
driven to flee by the hard-line leadership in East Berlin that has
rejected calls for reform.
   More than 100,000 East Germans have fled to West Germany so far
this year.
   Botho Sayn-Wittgenstein, president of the West German Red Cross,
returned from Prague on Friday. He said authorities were showing
willingness to deal with the crisis in a humanitarian spirit.
   Prague is considering an appeal to house refugees in other
buildings.
   Prague government spokesman Miroslav Pavel said the embassy
situation ``has slowly become a problem of public order in the
Czechoslovak capital.''
   ``We cannot overdramatize or build refugee camps while awaiting
other resolutions,'' Pavel said. But he said emergency shelter was
being considered.
   The more liberal Polish government has allowed East Germans in
Warsaw to move about the city freely.
   East Berlin lawyer Wolfgang Vogel visited Prague and Warsaw this
week and offered assurances the refugees could emigrate later if
they first returned to East Germany. But fewer than 10 percent of
refugees took up his offer.
   East Germans need no special permission to visit Prague, and
would-be emigrants _ disillusioned with widespread shortages and
harsh restrictions on travel and free expression _ appealed to the
West German Embassy to help them.
   West German border authorities said 447 more East Germans
arrived in southern Bavaria state in the 24 hours before Friday
noon, and 200 to 300 register daily in Budapest for travel to West
Germany.
   The number of refugees in Warsaw rose from 400 to 600 in one
day. Many have risked daring escapes across the Oder and Neisse
rivers.
</TEXT>
