<FIRST>u a PM-BakkerTrial Bjt   09-30 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bakker Trial, Bjt,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bakker: God Gave Him Vision Of Retreat</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CH1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker testified that his dream of a
Christian retreat was a vision from God, but the demands of fund
raising turned it into a nightmare.
   ``In the middle of the night I woke up,'' Bakker said Friday in
his first day on the witness stand for his fraud trial. ``It was a
vision or a dream, I don't know. God gave me the concept of the
Heritage Grand Partner Center and I began to sketch it.''
   The PTL founder said his biggest burden was raising funds to
build the Heritage USA retreat and theme park near Fort Mill, S.C.,
but he denied overselling partnerships in the project.
   Prosecutor Deborah Smith asked Bakker why he told television
viewers in 1984 that 50 percent of the 25,000 partnerships at the
Heritage Grand Hotel were taken when computer records showed fewer
than 4,000 had been bought.
   ``You were creating a false sense of urgency, weren't you, Mr.
Bakker?'' Ms. Smith asked.
   Bakker said PTL's computers typically ran six months behind,
adding: ``If you believe the computer records of Heritage USA, I
could sell you land under water in Florida.''
   Bakker is accused of fleecing followers of $158 million by
overselling ``lifetime partnerships'' at the ministry. The $1,000
partnerships entitled bearers to three nights lodging annually in
PTL facilities.
   Defense attorneys have claimed that the partnerships were not
sales transactions and that the money paid for them were gifts to
the ministry.
   Earlier in the trial, the prosecution presented several PTL
partners who said they sometimes were turned away when they tried
to use their lodging benefits. Prosecutors contend Bakker pocketed
$3.7 million of proceeds to fund his lavish lifestyle.
   On Friday, U.S. District Court Judge Robert Potter said Bakker
did not have proof to back up his calculations that there was room
for 211,062 lifetime partners. The judge refused to allow a chart
displaying the calculations to be presented to the jury.
   Bakker faces 120 years in prison and fines of more than $5
million if found guilty on all 24 counts of fraud and conspiracy.
   The evangelist often responded to prosecutors' questions by
saying he could not recall, had not been informed or that he
believed what he told television viewers.
   When Bakker said he could not recall getting a $50,000 Christmas
bonus in 1986, Smith said, ``Had your lifestyle become so
extravagant that you wouldn't have noticed a $50,000 bonus?''
   ``I did not look at my checkbook for several years,'' Bakker
said.
   Bakker also testified that fund raising at the ministry became a
nightmare.
   ``I think fund raising was my most burdensome job,'' he said.
   ``It never left me. You never ever, ever get away from the
pressure that you have to raise funds for next week, next month,
next year,'' he said.
   Bakker, who was briefly hospitalized during the trial after he
was reported to be suffering from hallucinations, took the stand
after his lawyers had presented more than 70 witnesses in his
defense.
   Neither his wife, Tammy Faye, nor his two children were in the
courtroom.
   In a low voice, Bakker described the roots of his PTL ministry,
which he resigned in a sex and money scandal in 1987. He then
described his vision to build the 2,400-acre Heritage USA.
   Bakker testified that he ``had confidence in God'' to supply
money for Heritage USA. When he left PTL, he said, the ministry's
budget was $160 million a year, ``which I think boils down to $3
million a week.''
   He also described his supervision of PTL's television network,
the Inspirational Network. ``When I left PTL, it was the largest
Christian network in the world,'' he said.
   ``TV is the most powerful medium in the world today,'' he said
at another point. ``I felt the message of Jesus Christ should be
propagated over that medium.''
</TEXT>
