<DOCNO> AP890930-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0507EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FBI-Skinheads     09-30 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI-Skinheads,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Five in `Skinhead' Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Justice Department officials say grand jury
indictments of five reputed members of a neo-Nazi ``skinhead''
group are a warning that lawmen are giving highest priority to
crushing crimes of hatred.
   The indictments involved allegations of vandalism at a Jewish
temple and the Jewish Community Center in Dallas, and attacks
against blacks and Hispanics at Robert E. Lee Park. The alleged
attacks occured last summer and fall, officials said.
   James P. Turner, acting assistant attorney general in the
Justice Department's civil rights division in Washington, announced
the indictments on Friday. Four of the five men are in custody,
federal authorities said.
   The five belong to a Dallas-based group called the Confederate
Hammerskins, officials said.
   The skinhead subculture emerged in London in the 1960s. Segments
of the movement took on Nazi overtones in 1985 and since have been
supported by and associated with the white supremacist Aryan Youth
Movement and White Aryan Resistance.
   ``These indictments involve interference with basic civil rights
because of a person's race, religion, national origin or ethnic
background,'' Turner said. ``Racial hate crimes are crimes against
the very idea of American freedom and democracy.''
   Turner added that ``President Bush and Attorney General (Dick)
Thornburgh have made it clear that these prosecutions of this type
rank right up there with the war on drugs as a federal law
enforcement priority.''
   The indictments bring to 16 the number of Confederate
Hammerskins associates charged in the grand jury investigation that
began in February following months of hate crimes in north Texas
and surrounding areas. Seven have pleaded guilty to charges in
connection with violence last summer and fall.
   The white supremacy group first appeared in Dallas less than two
years ago when Sean Christian Tarrant, one of the defendants,
formed the Hammerskins.
   The three-count indictment names Tarrant, Jon Lance Jordan,
Michael Lewis Lawrence, Christopher Barry Greer and Daniel Alvis
Wood. It alleged two separate conspiracies to commit acts of
violence.
   Each of the two charges carries a maximum sentence of 10 years
imprisonment and a $250,000 fine.
   Lawrence, Jordan and Wood also were charged with using a firearm
in a violent crime.
   Jordan remained at large Saturday, said Barry Kowalski, an
attorney with the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   Mark Briskman, Dallas regional director of the B'nai B'rith
Anti-Defamation League, said he believes that the federal
prosecutions ``will drive a stake into the heart of the vampire.''
   ``I think that this sends a very clear message to bigots and the
organized hate community that these kinds of activities are not
going to be tolerated,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
