<DOCNO> AP890930-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0511EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     09-30 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Followers Brace for Another Saga: Where to Bury Marcos</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of Ferdinand E. Marcos was expected to
be the end of a saga for his followers, but they say it's turning
into the beginning of another one _ when and where he'll be buried.
   ``President Marcos' death is not the end of the story for me,''
said aide Arturo Aruiza, a colonel in the Philippine Army who
advised Marcos for more than 20 years. ``My job is with the
president. Now I must stay with his body.''
   Long before the chronically ill former Philippines president
died of cardiac arrest Thursday at the age of 72, the 20 or so
members of his staff were pondering life without him.
   Some, such as Aruiza, hoped to return to the Philippines. Others
are seeking residency in the United States or staying on with
Marcos' widow, Imelda.
   But now, with the fate of Marcos' body uncertain, many employees
said they had put their plans on hold.
   ``What will I do? I'll wait for my appeal,'' said spokesman
Leoni Tan, who has appealed an immigration judge's denial of his
request for political asylum here. ``It looks like I'll have plenty
to do for Ma`am,'' he said, referring to Mrs. Marcos.
   Marcos' corpse has been lying in a bronze casket in the living
room of the family home since Thursday. Hundreds of people have
viewed the body, with the novena to continue through Friday.
   There are no plans for burial. Mrs. Marcos says it's the only
way to ensure it would return to the Philippines if the opportunity
arises.
   ``My plan has always been to bring him back,'' she said. ``I
have committed myself to what is Ferdinand's right to rest in peace
in his motherland.''
   Initially, President Corazon Aquino said Marcos' return _ even
dead _ could destabilize the administration she's headed since a
popular revolt ousted Marcos in 1986.
   But later, Mrs. Aquino softened her rhetoric slightly, saying
she might consider the return later if political conditions were
right. She also said she might consider allowing Mrs. Marcos and
her three children to return.
   ``There is nothing that would prohibit the temporary display of
a body in a private home if it does not create a health hazard or a
nuisance,'' Hawaii Attorney General Warren Price said. A court
ruling might be required to define ``temporary,'' he added.
   Neighbors in the usually tranquil neighborhood of Makiki Heights
hope Marcos is buried _ somewhere _ soon.
   ``We don't mind an appropriate memorial service. Two weeks is
fine, two years is too long,'' said John Steelquist, chairman of
the neighborhood board.
   Steelquist said the neighborhood was worried Marcos' would end
up like his mother, Dona Josefa Edralin, who died in the
Philippines in May 1988 but has never been buried because Marcos
could not return to preside over the funeral.
   Several pro-Marcos Filipino arrived Friday to pay their
respects. Others, such as Joan Still, a tourist from Cleveland,
Tenn., visited ``out of curiosity.''
   ``Mrs. Marcos was very warm, I offered my prayers and she
thanked me for coming,'' Mrs. Still said. ``I feel like he did
wrong, but maybe he asked God to forgive him.''
   In the Philippines, officials said Marcos' death might encourage
his family and former associates to settle claims made by the
Philippine government out of court to avoid costly legal battles.
   Marcos attorney John Bartko said the family remains anxious to
resolve the dispute, since it could allow their return to the
Philippines. However, he said there were no plea bargaining talks
taking place regarding Mrs. Marcos' U.S. criminal case.
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent in a New York court to federal
racketeering charges alleging she and her husband stole nearly $200
million from their impoverished country and stashed it in the
United States.
   A lawyer for the Philippines said a $5 billion civil fraud and
racketeering lawsuit brought against Marcos in Los Angeles would go
forward.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
