<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Romania     09-30 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Romania,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Romania Urged Defending Socialism When Solidarity Premier Nominated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after President Wojciech Jaruzelski
nominated the East bloc's first non-communist prime minister,
Romania's leader proposed Warsaw Pact action aimed at ``defending
socialism,'' documents show.
   The documents, published Friday in the Polish press, said
Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu summoned Poland's ambassador
at midnight Aug. 19 and told him: ``As a Communist Party, a
socialist country, we cannot consider this an internal affair of
Poland alone.''
   In a response sent to Romania after the meeting, the Polish
Communist Party rejected Romania's protest as ``unfounded'' and an
``unjustified attempt at undermining our country's credibility as
an ally,'' a document said.
   Two documents, one appearing to be a Polish diplomatic report
about the incident and the second, the response of the communist
Polish United Workers Party, were published by the pro-Solidarity
Gazeta Wyborcza newspaper. They were picked up by the Polish news
agency PAP.
   Poland's Communist Party criticized publication of the documents.
   On Aug. 19, Jaruzelski nominated Solidarity journalist Tadeusz
Mazowiecki as prime minister. Czeslaw Kiszczak had resigned from
the post after a futile three-week effort to form a communist-led
government.
   ``Making it possible for Solidarity to come to power is
discordant with the scientific, revolutionary concept of socialist
construction and serves the most reactionary circles,'' said a
statement read to Polish Ambassador Jerzy Wozniak in Bucharest by
Romanian Communist Party secretary, Ion Stojan.
   Romanian communists turned that same night to leaders of the
other Warsaw Pact Communist Parties ``to express grave concern and
to jointly act in favor of preventing a serious situation in
Poland, in favor of defending socialism and the Polish nation,''
PAP said.
   There was no indication what type of united action Ceausescu
envisioned. A similar justification was used in the 1968 invasion
of Czechoslovakia, in which Soviet bloc troops crushed the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms of Alexander Dubcek. Romania was the only member
of the bloc that did not join the invasion.
   The late Soviet leader Leonid Brezhnev had invoked the Brezhnev
Doctrine, allowing Moscow to intervene militarily if the Kremlin
considered communism ``in danger'' in other Warsaw Pact countries.
   Warsaw Pact countries did not move to interfere with
Mazowiecki's government. Soviet leaders said the naming of the new
government was a matter of internal Polish politics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
