<FIRST>r a PM-USAirProbe     09-30 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USAir Probe,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Flight Recorder Differs From Voice Recorder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The flight recorder of the USAir plane that
crashed at LaGuardia Airport last week indicates that the plane's
rudder was misaligned before the aborted takeoff, a newspaper
reported today.
   The cockpit voice recorder shows the pilots, while conducting a
pre-flight checklist, found the cockpit gauge showed the rudder was
properly centered, The New York Times reported in today editions.
   Citing unidentified industry sources, the Times said the
conflicting evidence raised the question of whether the discrepancy
was due to a mechanical problem or whether the crew made a mistake
in reading the gauge.
   The flight recorder steadily records data on 70 of the plane's
conditions, including the position of the rudder.
   The rudder position on the 737-400 has become the focus of an
investigation of the Sept. 20 crash in which two passengers were
killed and 45 of 61 on board were hurt, the paper said.
   The National Transportation Safety Board earlier this week said
the trim actuator _ operated from the cockpit and which helps
position the rudder _ had been found in the extreme-left position
on the wreck.
   That would have made the plane veer to the left during takeoff
as has been reported by the captain of the jet.
   The pilot has said the veer and an unusual vibration he felt led
him to take over the controls from the co-pilot and abort the
takeoff.
</TEXT>
