<FIRST>r i PM-PLO-Soviets     09-30 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PLO-Soviets,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Says Moscow Willing to Play Host to PLO-Israel Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze sent PLO chief Yasser Arafat a message suggesting that
a dialogue between the PLO and Israel could take place in Moscow, a
Palestinian news agency said.
   The Palestinian news agency WAFA said the message from
Shevardnadze was passed to Mahmoud Abbas, a member of the executive
committee of the Palestine Liberation Organization, by the Soviet
charge d'affaires in Tunis.
   Arafat received it on Friday, the agency said.
   Shevardnadze made a similar proposal Thursday at the U.N.
General Assembly in New York.
   Abbas termed the offer an important step in the peace process
and urged ``the Israeli government to respond favorably and without
preconditions,'' WAFA said.
   The Israeli government has refused to meet with the PLO, which
it considers a terrorist group.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has proposed that a meeting
between Israel and the PLO on ending the 21-month-old Palestinian
uprising against Israeli rule of the occupied territories be held
in Cairo.
   At least 575 Palestinians and 40 Israelis have died in the Arab
revolt.
</TEXT>
