<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0547EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     09-30 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>300 Sinhalese Extremists Surrender, 3 Die In Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 300 Sinhalese extremists
have surrendered in the army's 4-day-old cease-fire, but other
radicals launched more attacks and killed three people, the
government said today.
   A government statement said the extremists had surrendered since
Wednesday, when the military halted operations against the People's
Liberation Front hoping to persuade the ultranationalists to
initiate peace talks.
   The cease-fire was to expire early today, but President
Ranasinghe Premadasa extended it until 6 a.m. Tuesday. The Front
has rejected the truce.
   The statement said Front members killed at least three people,
including a security force member, on Friday and early today in
central and southern Sri Lanka.
   The deaths brought to 17 the number of people killed since
Wednesday by the Front, which opposes the Sinhalese-dominated
government's peace plan granting limited autonomy to Tamils in the
island's northern and eastern areas.
   Tamils want a separate nation and complain of discrimination by
the majority Sinhalese in jobs and education.
   The Sinhalese extremists also burned 12 post offices, 11 other
government buildings and three government vehicles over the past
four days, the government said without elaborating.
   On Friday, 14 government offices, 10 state-owned buses, seven
post offices and a factory were reported burned by the extremists
who have waged a 2-year-old battle to overthrow the government.
   The Sinhalese war and the military's counter-operations have
cost more than 5,000 lives since 1987, the year the government
reached the peace agreement with the Tamil minority and invited
Indian troops to help disarm Tamil rebels.
   Ultranationalist Sinhalese launched their campaign of
assassinations and terror that year, accusing the government of
making too many concessions to Tamil secessionists. The Front also
protests the deployment of Indian peacekeeping soldiers, saying
they compromise the country's independence.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Sinhalese make up 75 percent and dominate the government and the
military.
   At least 11,000 people including 1,000 Indian soldiers have been
killed since the Tamil separatist war began in 1983.
</TEXT>
