<FIRST>r a PM-TrainDerailment     09-30 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Derailment,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Saying Little On Fatal Train-Firetruck Collision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CATLETT, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The collision between an Amtrak train and a
firetruck was the third in five years at a rural crossing, but one
official said the crash that killed two firefighters was
``unavoidable.''
   State and federal investigators declined to speculate on the
cause of Thursday evening's wreck, but they said there was no sign
the train crew was at fault.
   ``There is no indication that there was any improper action on
the part of the train's crew that in any way led to the accident,''
Amtrak spokesman Michael Stewart said.
   The Amtrak Crescent, carrying 379 passengers and a crew of 20,
was en route from New York to Atlanta and New Orleans when it
struck a Catlett Volunteer Fire Department truck about 50 miles
southwest of Washington, D.C.
   The National Transportation Safety Board and the state police
are investigating the accident, in which 12 of the train's 16 cars
and two locomotives derailed.
   The track was reopened Friday afternoon.
   A preliminary investigation by Amtrak showed the train was
traveling at 77 mph at the time of the collision, just below the
speed limit of 79 mph, Stewart said.
   Local authorities said it was the third collision in five years
at the crossing on a private road near Virginia 28. The previous
two did not cause any injuries.
   The crash highlighted the danger of the crossing, authorities
said. There is a railroad crossing sign at the junction, but no
crossing bar or warning light.
   ``It was an unavoidable accident,'' Fauquier County Deputy
Sheriff Robert Mosier said. ``The crossing sits on a steep grade,
so the driver couldn't stop to look. He had his lights on and the
siren running next to his ear, not to mention the sound of the
truck's motor.''
   State police spokeswoman Lucy Caldwell said the firetruck
carrying five firefighters was responding to a report of a car fire
near a home on the other side of the tracks.
   Stewart said the train sounded its horn when it approached the
crossing.
   Firefighters Mark Miller, 23, the driver of the truck, and Matt
Smith, 22, the front-seat passenger, both of Catlett, died at the
scene.
   ``It really shakes you. It's devastating,'' Catlett Fire Chief
Clyde Lomax said. ``We're just trying to stay together, talk this
thing out.''
   Seven people _ two firefighters and five passengers _ remained
hospitalized early today.
   One firefighter, Ernest Colbert, was listed in serious condition
at Fairfax Hospital. Another, Michael S. Kirk, 21, was in fair
condition at Washington Hospital Center.
   The fifth fireman, Frankie Herndon, was treated at a local
hospital and released.
   Caldwell said a total of 68 train passengers and 10 crew members
were sent to hospitals, as well as the three firefighters. Another
80 or so passengers were treated for minor injuries at the scene,
she said.
   Kirk, interviewed by telephone from his hospital bed Friday,
said he could not recall the crash.
   ``I don't remember anything,'' Kirk said. ``The last thing I
remember I was mowing the grass ... then I was here.''
   Last year 594 people were killed and 2,344 were injured in 5,820
grade-crossing wrecks nationwide. In Virginia, six people were
killed and 41 were injured in 110 crossing crashes in 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
