<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0608EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FernaldSettlement     09-30 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald Settlement,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Judge Approves Fernald Plant Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE McDONALD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for neighbors of the Fernald uranium
processing plant says he hopes a judge's approval of a $78 million
settlement leads to early monitoring of health risks in the area.
   ``If early detection of cancer saves even one life, it's worth
it,'' said Stanley Chesley, who led lawyers for 14,000 plaintiffs
in the 4-year-old class-action lawsuit.
   U.S. District Judge S. Arthur Spiegel filed an order Friday
saying he found fair and reasonable a settlement to the suit
offered by the U.S. Department of Energy, owner of the Feed
Materials Production Center. The settlement will support long-term
medical studies of residents within five miles of the plant.
   The 38-year-old facility located 18 miles northwest of
Cincinnati processes uranium for use in nuclear reactors and
weapons.
   The Energy Department offered June 30 to settle a $300 million
claim by neighbors who said radioactive pollution from the plant
inflicted emotional suffering and reduced their property values.
Spiegel ruled that the settlement is limited to those two issues.
   Chesley has said lawyers expect medical monitoring to last 30 to
40 years and track such ailments as lung cancer and kidney disease.
   Claims by individual residents were certified as a class-action
lawsuit in September 1986.
   Spiegel rejected the government's contention that the settlement
protects the Energy Department from claims by neighbors for the
cost of cleaning up radioactive contamination of their property. He
said the neighbors are free to file such claims.
   Henry Gill Jr., the Energy Department's chief lawyer in the
case, declined to comment Friday from his Washington office, saying
he had not seen the judge's order.
   Spiegel dismissed objections to the settlement by Ruetgers-Nease
Chemical Co. and Delta Steel Corp., commercial neighbors of the
Fernald plant. Spiegel ruled that the companies lack legal standing
to object to the settlement because they don't own the property on
which they operate in the five-mile radius set as a requirement for
participation in the lawsuit.
   William Kennedy, a lawyer for Ruetgers-Nease, also declined
comment from his Philadelphia office, saying he hadn't seen
Spiegel's order.
   Spiegel appointed three people to serve as court-supervised
masters and trustees to oversee implementation of the settlement.
</TEXT>
