<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0616EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-ArmsTalks     09-30 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Talks,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>Positive Mood As Arms Talks Resume, But Particulars Unresolved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite optimism over prospects for a superpower
treaty to cut long-range nuclear weapons, the chief U.S. delegate
said hundreds of disagreements must still be resolved.
   Talks on the treaty resumed Friday and Ambassador Richard Burt
told reporters after a one-on-one meeting with his Soviet
counterpart Yuri Nazarkin that the ``spirit of Jackson Hole has
moved to Geneva.''
   He referred to last weekend's talks in Wyoming between Secretary
of State James Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze. Those meetings ended with senior aides on both sides
saying a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty was within reach.
   Burt said, however, his team must read the ``fine print'' of the
Soviet proposals that prompted the optimistic assessments.
   Detailed negotiations begin Monday with a full meeting of both
delegations.
   The new round of talks is the 12th since negotiations began in
March 1985.
   Asked about prospects for completing the treaty by the
superpower summit _ scheduled for late spring or early summer next
year _ Burt replied that it ``would be a major mistake for us to
negotiate against an artificial deadline.''
   He said Shevardnadze's remarks in Wyoming ``apparently'' mean
that Moscow dropped its linkage between a treaty and an accord on
defense and space issues.
   The Soviets said in Wyoming that they would drop a demand that
the United States curb work on a space-based missile defense
program before a treaty on long-range missiles is completed.
   ``We need to understand very clearly what the Soviets are and
are not proposing here,'' Burt said.
   He made plain that Washington was not enthusiastic about the
Soviet offer to take the issue of submarine-launched cruise
missiles out of a treaty. The United States does not believe these
missiles can be effectively monitored, he said.
   ``We have heard some Soviet ideas and as Secretary Baker has
said, our first reaction is positive. Our job here is to read the
fine print and fully understand what the Soviets are telling us.''
   The draft treaty text covers more than 450 pages, he said.
   ``There are hundreds of disagreements on a range of issues. Some
of them are big, important questions and some are small technical
disputes,'' Burt said.
</TEXT>
