<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0620EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-PENMeeting     09-30 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PEN Meeting,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three More East Bloc Ethnic Groups Accepted By Writers Association</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three more ethnic groups in the East bloc gained
representation in the PEN international writers association, and
Soviet delegates attended the association's meeting for the first
time.
   Concluding its weeklong congress Friday, PEN accepted Ukrainian,
Czech and Slovak chapters as members.
   A 65-year quarrel ended in May with the admission of the first
chapter from the Soviet Union, based in Moscow. PEN had kept out
the Soviet Union, citing that country's persecution of writers and
other intellectuals. Moscow had regarded the authors' group as
anti-communist.
   For the first time, two Soviet delegates from the Moscow chapter
attended the Canadian congress, held in Toronto and Montreal.
   The Ukrainian chapter will be based in Kiev in the Soviet
Ukraine but, based on language, will accept Ukrainian writers from
anywhere. Mykola Vingranovsky, its representative, said in a
statement that the chapter will work to keep the Ukrainian language
alive in modern life.
   A Lithuanian chapter also was admitted in May to join Latvian
and Estonian chapters that existed in exile.
   PEN's international secretary, Alexander Blokh, said the Baltic
chapters are not considered part of the Soviet Union for PEN's
administrative purposes.
   ``It is not a country that is represented; it is a literature,''
he said in an interview.
   The Czech chapter, dormant since the 1968 Soviet intervention,
was reactivated and the new Slovak chapter was recognized
separately at its request.
   Czech playwright Vaclav Havel, a rights activist sentenced to
nine months imprisonment in February, said in a message to the
congress that the separation was in the interest of both
literatures, no matter how close they might be.
   Czechoslovakia denied Havel a passport. He was represented by an
empty chair Thursday at a discussion to which he had been invited.
   Bulgarian, Hungarian, Polish and East German chapters also exist.
   While PEN expressed cautious optimism about the new contacts, it
expressed concern about threats to freedom of expression in the Far
East.
   Thomas von Vegesack, chairman of the International PEN Writers
in Prison Committee, told the congress, ``We have had a long, long
list of writers and journalists who have been jailed in China.''
   He said the latest word was 33 new cases of writers imprisoned
in China since the pro-democracy demonstrations.
   A resolution passed this week said PEN was appalled by the
events of Tiananmen Square and reports of torture routinely used
against those arrested.
   Von Vegesack reported that his committee had a list of 358 cases
throughout the world, with 78 people released and 127 new cases
since March.
   ``This is the highest figure the committee has had on its list
in five years,'' he wrote.
   He noted that before glasnost, Europe was the continent with the
most cases. ``Today, most of our new cases are in the Far East,''
he wrote.
   Von Vegesack told reporters he knew of 41 writers and
journalists arrested in South Korea.
   A resolution passed by PEN said it was distressed by reports of
the ``disappearance'' of dissidents and asked the Burmese
government to cease what PEN views as the persecution of writers.
   PEN, founded in 1921, has about 11,000 members in more than 90
chapters organized along language lines. It is an international
association of poets, playwrights, editors, essayists and novelists.
   The association is holding its convention in Canada for the
first time. The Canadian English-speaking chapter acted as host in
Toronto. The group then traveled to Montreal on Wednesday where the
French-speaking chapter was host.
   A PEN resolution expressed ``anxiety'' that a possible
plebiscite on Puerto Rico's political future ``as drafted up to now
ignores the linguistic and cultural reality of the Puerto Rican
people.''
</TEXT>
