<FIRST>r p PM-PhoenixElection     09-30 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phoenix Election,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phoenix Mayor's Reelection Bid Could Be Hurt by Unpopular Ventures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Phoenix Mayor Terry Goddard's bid for a fourth
two-year term could hinge on his opponents' ability to capitalize
on the popular mayor's support for unpopular projects.
   Those projects include an amphitheater that neighbors opposed, a
Grand Prix auto race that snarled downtown traffic for weeks and a
multibillion-dollar mass-transit project rejected by voters earlier
this year.
   But a Phoenix Gazette poll two weeks before Tuesday's election
showed Goddard had the support of 54 percent of the city's
registered voters, with only 10 percent for Republican Party
chairman Burton Kruglick, the strongest opponent. About 32 percent
were undecided.
   The son of former Gov. Sam Goddard, who heads the state
Democratic Party, the 42-year-old mayor burst onto the political
scene early in the decade when he led successful campaigns against
a state gasoline tax and for district elections for City Council
members.
   First elected mayor in 1983, Goddard has gained national stature
in recent months as president of the National League of Cities.
   But his challengers _ Kruglick and Norris Inman, a real estate
broker _ claim Goddard has supported grandiose plans that taxpayers
neither want nor can afford.
   Kruglick, 64, said his research showed nearly half the voters
``felt that the city had no direction, was too political and was
high-handed.''
   Goddard scoffs at the idea of a voter backlash.
   ``There are a few people who want to stand up on a street corner
and shout, but believe me, most people I talk to are neutral or
very enthusiastic about what we've done,'' he said recently.
   The city election is legally non-partisan, but Kruglick,
recently endorsed by President Bush, maintains that a Republican
challenger was needed because Goddard is a high-profile Democrat
with designs on the governor's office.
   Inman, who never has held public office, was defeated by a 2-1
margin in his only other campaign, a bid for the City Council in
1987.
   Goddard's support for a proposed amphitheater in a northwest
Phoenix neighborhood that wanted no part of it was defeated when
the City Council rejected the proposal.
   A proposition on Tuesday's ballot would prohibit future councils
from spending more than $3 million for amphitheaters or sports
arenas without voter approval.
   Goddard also was on the losing side when voters resoundingly
defeated multibillion-dollar proposals to expand the
mass-transportation system and to develop the dry Salt River bed
through Phoenix.
   Goddard supports city financing of a downtown baseball stadium,
another issue on the ballot.
   Voters will decide whether the city should spend no more than
$100 million toward the cost of either a football-baseball stadium
or a baseball-only stadium. If the measure is approved, property
taxes would be raised a maximum of 10 cents per $100 valuation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
