<FIRST>r a PM-KKK-Highway     09-30 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-KKK-Highway,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Carolina Refuses KKK Offer to `Adopt-a-Highway'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state refused the Ku Klux Klan
permission to join an Adopt-a-Highway clean-up program that would
have allowed the group to post its name on signs along a stretch of
road running through a black neighborhood.
   State Transportation Secretary Jim Harrington said Friday he was
denying the request from the Rockingham County chapter of The
Invisible Empire Knights of the Ku Klux Klan to adopt a section of
U.S. 158, about 100 miles northwest of Raleigh.
   Under the program, the state puts up eye-catching,
green-and-white road signs naming the group or business that has
pledged to clean the adopted stretch of road four times a year.
   The Klan asked for a 3.4-mile stretch of road through a
predominately black neighborhood that leads to its rally site.
   Rockey Chapman, a leader of the Klan chapter, vowed to fight the
decision, and he was supported by the state branch of the American
Civil Liberties Union.
   ``Here we are trying to do something civic, and they slap us in
the face,'' Chapman said. ``I strongly feel that I have not been
given my constitutional rights. I do want this road, and I won't
stop until I get it.''
   ``For government to adopt censorship is to do a Klan-like thing
and literally give the victory to the Klan,'' said Jim Shields,
executive director of the North Carolina branch of the ACLU.
   The state has 4,756 volunteer groups participating in the
clean-up program.
   ``I don't understand why they are refusing me,'' said Chapman,
identified as the Exalted Cyclops of the Klan's Reidsville Southern
Alliance.
   ``I've got the same intentions behind me that everyone else
does, it's just the name that's scaring them, and it shouldn't,''
Chapman said. ``We are trying to help humans in the world today _
white humans.''
</TEXT>
