<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon 3rdLd-Writethru   09-30 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0487,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Fahd Calls on Lebanese Legislators to Make Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to CORRECT that Fahd speech read by his
foreign minister. Pickup 10 graf, ``Some of...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese legislators who have survived
a 14{-year-old civil war gathered today for peace talks, but they
divided over the deployment of Syrian forces and Moslem demands for
greater political power.
   King Fahd, in an opening address read by Foreign Minister Prince
Saud al Fasisal, called on the Christian and Moslem lawmakers to
set aside their differences and end fighting that has killed more
than 150,000 people.
   ``Now that the situation has shifted from the arena of warriors
to the negotiators' table, it is high time we moved from trading
artillery shells and accusations to hasten the peacemaking,'' the
king's message said.
   Fahd is a member of a three-nation committee mandated by the
22-member Arab League to end the bloodletting and reconcile
Lebanon's feuding factions.
   An Arab League-sponsored peace plan included a Sept. 22
cease-fire that ended the latest round of fighting between Syrian
forces and Christian army units under Gen. Michel Aoun, who heads
the Christian Cabinet. More than 920 people have died in the last
six months of intensive shelling in Lebanon.
   Fahd, King Hassan II of Morocco and President Chadli Bendjedid
of Algeria formulated the seven-point peace plan that includes a
``national reconciliation charter'' of political reforms that the
Lebanese parliamentarians will debate.
   The Fahd speech delivered at the Conference Palace in this
mountain resort said the blueprint is ``a realistic and practical
basis for a solution'' to the conflict that broke out in 1975.
   The Taif meeting is the first by Lebanon's parliament outside
the country.
   By holding the talks on neutral ground, the Arab League has
sought to reduce sectarian pressures on the legislators which have
been a major factor in the collapse of earlier initiatives.
   The Fahd message to the parliamentarians said: ``The night of
Lebanon's tragedy has gone on much too long, and the dawn ... will
come sooner or later. The decision is up to you. Lebanon and all
Lebanese will be the winners if you agree among yourselves. The
world is closely following your historic meeting.''
   Some of the Lebanese deputies who arrived in Taif late Friday
said the meeting would last three-to-10 days.
   Conference sources said 63 of Lebanon's 73 surviving legislators
_ 33 Christians and 30 Moslems _ were attending the Taif
conference. Three Shiite Moslem and seven Christian deputies failed
to show up.
   ``No one has refused to come, but some gave medical reasons for
not attending,'' Saud said.
   Twenty-five of the deputies in the 99-seat Parliament have been
killed or died of natural causes since the last elections in 1972.
Another seat was held by Amin Gemayel, whose six-year term as
president expired on Sept. 22, 1988. The war has prevented
elections since then and Lebanon has no head of state.
   Christian-Moslem differences split the government into the rival
camps.
   Before the deputies left the Lebanese capital Beirut on Friday,
Lebanon's acting prime minister, Salim Hoss, said the Taif meeting
``could be the last chance for peace in Lebanon.''
   Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini told reporters upon arriving
in Taif: ``We are determined to reach a unified concept on the
issue of political reform to achieve national reconciliation.''
   While agreeing to the meeting, Christians said they would not
discuss political reform unless Syria agreed to a timetable for
withdrawing its 40,000 troops from Lebanon. They arrived under a
1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate but soon allied with Moslem
militias in fighting the Christians.
   Syria has said it will not consider a withdrawal until a united
government emerges in Lebanon and the Moslems are given a larger
share of power in constitutional reforms.
   The proposed reforms call for Lebanon's Maronites, the dominant
Christian sect, to surrender the privileges they have held since
independence from France in 1943. They would share power equally
with the country's Moslems.
   In 1943, the Christians were considered the majority. But
Moslems now comprise an estimated 55 percent of Lebanon's 4 million
people.
   The latest outbreak in fighting began in March, when Aoun
blockaded illegal militia-run ports saying they deprived the state
of more than $100 million yearly in lost revenues. The
Syrian-Moslem alliance responded by blockading the 310-square-mile
Christian enclave in and around Beirut.
</TEXT>
