<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 0914EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-China     09-30 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Muted National Day Celebrations Begin in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese today began a long holiday weekend
celebrating the 40th anniversary of Communist rule, but most were
barred from festivities in Tiananmen Square which remains closed to
the general public.
   Many Chinese said they had no special plans for the four-day
weekend.
   ``I've borrowed a whole stack of books. I'm going to read and
sleep in,'' said a college student.
   ``We'll spend the weekend resting, just like everybody else,''
another student said.
   Some private entreprenuers said they would work as usual.
   Unlike previous years, most Chinese will not be allowed into
central Beijing's Tiananmen Square to see the elaborate, colorful
flower arrangements.
   In past years, the square teemed with people admiring the
displays and posing for souvenir snapshots. This year, however,
only groups who have permission are allowed into the square.
   Tiananmen has been closed to the general public since June 3-4,
when troops shot their way into the capital to crush the popular
pro-democracy movement and retake Tiananmen from the students.
   This morning thousands of people, including foreign tourists and
low-level officials from the countryside, arrived at the square in
a caravan of buses. Kindergarten children played games amid the
flower arrangements while men flew long kites in the warm autumn
breeze.
   Rows of red flags fluttered in the square and atop the landmarks
that border Tiananmen: the Great Hall of the People, the wall of
the Forbidden City and the history museum.
   Throughout the city, colored flags and China's national flag _
red with five stars _ flew on rooftops, and long red banners
encouraged people to ``warmly celebrate the 40th anniversary of the
People's Republic of China.''
   Massive flower arrangements with patriotic slogans such as
``socialism is good'' have been placed at main intersections.
Official reports say about 1 million pots of flowers have been set
out throughout the capital.
   China's top leaders planned a reception tonight for foreign
diplomats, businessmen and journalists, and Chinese model workers
and dignitaries.
   This year's festivities have been drastically cut back from the
activities that were expected to celebrate four decades of
Communist rule.
   A military parade, which was to have been the first in five
years, was canceled without explanation. The main activities will
be dances performed by thousands of workers and students on Sunday
morning in Tiananmen Square and a massive fireworks show in the
evening.
   This afternoon, 300 students at Beijing Normal University, one
of the hotbeds of student activism this spring, practiced dances
one last time.
   A second-year economics major sitting in the bleachers watching
her classmates practicing in large circles in the field below said
the dancers were selected on the basis of their dancing ability and
political purity.
   But nearly the entire school was involved in the seven-week
pro-democracy movement, and the student, who did not give her name,
said there were at least a few among the dancers who had
participated in the movement.
   Students at the Normal University and other schools in northwest
Beijing's university district said the campuses had little of the
holiday atmosphere of past National Days.
   At Beijing University, also a center of student activism this
spring, a second-year law student said with a sigh, ``Last year we
celebrated National Day with such enthusiasm.''
   A sign at the school's announcement board area, which this
spring was plastered with hundreds of big-character poster calling
for democracy and other reforms, said a dance would be held tonight.
   But the law student, who also did not give her name, said no
other activities were planned because the semester has not yet
started.
   Classes were delayed at Beijing University until mid-October,
partly to avoid any disturbance during the National Day festivities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
