<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia 3rdLd-Writethru   09-30 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0486,0665</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Report Major Offensive; Government Plans Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 9th pvs, ``Our intention...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT that
Samrin president, not prime minister. Pickup 10th, ``A Western...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NATE THAYER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARANYAPRATHET, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Non-communist guerrillas said
they launched a major offensive in Cambodia that captured two towns
and 10 other positions from the pro-Vietnamese government.
   The claim came soon after Vietnam said its last troops had
pulled out of Cambodia, where they fought the guerrillas for more
than a decade. The battle is now being waged by soldiers of the
government Vietnam installed.
   Also today, a Vietnam News Agency report monitored in Bangkok,
Thailand, said Cambodia's government in Phnom Penh plans to hold
general elections at the end of the year whether or not a political
solution to the insurgency is found.
   A spokesman for the Khmer People's National Liberation Front,
Abdulgaffar Peang-Meth, said 5,000 guerrilla fighters attacked five
towns and other positions along Highway 69, which parallels
Cambodia's western border.
   Gen. Dien Del, acting commander of the front, said his fighters
knocked out tanks, overran 10 army positions flanking the highway
and seized a district capital, Thmar Puok. The Vietnamese army left
that town six days ago.
   At the town of Banteay Chmar, which Dien Del said was also
seized, the front captured a warehouse with 1,000 weapons, he said.
   Dien Del said the attackers sustained light casualties and
inflicted heavy losses on Cambodia's forces, estimated at 4,500
soldiers. He said one Soviet-built T-54 tank was destroyed, two
disabled and a fourth captured.
   His claims could not be independently verified.
   ``Our intention is to test the strength of the government of
President Heng Samrin and force Phnom Penh to the negotiating
table,'' the general said.
   A Western diplomat said that if true, the fall of Thmar Puok
would be a ``major victory'' for the front.
   A Western relief official based in the border town of
Aranyaprathet said heavy shelling could be heard near the key
border town from early morning.
   He said the front's vast refugee camp of Site 2, 30 miles to the
north, was closed to relief workers for fear of possible
retaliation by government gunners. Site 2 is the largest camp on
the border, housing 140,000 people.
   ``We will know more in the next couple of days,'' the relief
official said. ``At the moment it is difficult to judge how much is
true and how much is propaganda.'' He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The general also discussed the assault on Sisophon, located at
the junction of highways 69 and 5 and at the southern end of the
38-mile-long and 10-to-25-mile deep area the front says it is
attacking.
   He said Sisophon was listed as among the five major objectives
of the offensive and was attacked for ``psychological warfare
reasons.''
   He said there would be no attempt to capture it. Earlier, front
officers said their troops had already entered Sisophon. The
northernmost town is Banteay Chmar. The other targeted towns are
Svey Chiek and Kandoun.
   The diplomat said the front may have timed the push with drives
by its guerrilla coalition partners _ the communist Khmer Rouge and
a group loyal to resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk _ in
other areas along the Thai-Cambodian border.
   The front claims to have 16,000 fighters. The strongest
guerrilla group, the Khmer Rouge, fields up to 40,000, according to
Western estimates.
   Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia and ousted the Khmer Rouge in
late 1978, said it completed withdrawal of its troops on Tuesday.
But the guerrillas say thousands of Vietnamese have stayed behind.
   Some diplomats say the poorly trained and equipped Cambodian
army may not be able to beat back the guerrillas without Vietnamese
support.
   The Khmer Rouge has recently claimed a series of battle
successes against Cambodian army units, which they say were
supported by Vietnamese troops.
</TEXT>
