<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Lithuania     09-30 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Lithuania,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Republic Demands Negotiations on Military Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislature of the Baltic republic Lithuania
has ordered government officials to negotiate with Moscow to permit
youths to perform their military service close to home, an activist
said today.
   Rimantas Kanapenas, head of Sajudis political movement's press
center, said in a telephone interview that the resolution seeks to
have all Lithuanian military recruits serve in their home republic
or one of the two other Baltic republics beginning next year.
   Under the resolution approved Friday, the republic's Council of
Ministers, or Cabinet, is required to open talks with the Soviet
Defense Ministry, he said.
   The issue of having Baltic recruits serve close to home has been
raised by Sajudis and other People's Front organizations in the
Baltic republics of Latvia and Estonia, which are clamoring for
sovereignty from Moscow in their political and economic affairs.
   Soviet Defense Ministry officials have scoffed at the idea,
saying the county needs a unified defense rather than one based on
regional interests.
</TEXT>
