<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1001EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Senate-Census     09-30 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Senate-Census,230</SECOND>
<TEXT>
   Senate Votes to Bar Counting of Illegals in Census
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Census Bureau would be barred from
counting illegal aliens in next year's census under a measure
approved by the Senate in a decision that could affect the
redrawing of congressional districts.
   ``An occupying army would qualify'' for being counted in the
census under current rules, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said Friday
as the Senate approved the legislation on a voice vote and attached
it to a $17.3 billion money bill for the Commerce, State and
Justice Departments.
   A move to table, or kill, the measure was defeated, 50-41
   The 435 seats in the House of Representatives will be
reallocated among the states following the 1990 census, with the
most populous states as always getting the most seats.
   Thus lawmakers from states with few illegal aliens would like to
see them omitted from next year's count.
   The measure sponsored by Sen. Richard C. Shelby, D-Ala., would
bar the use of funds contained in the Commerce Department
appropriation for counting the illegals in the census.
   Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., said some states would
lose congressional seats because they have few illegals.
   ``This policy simply does not make any sense,'' Dole said.
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., said, however, that a number of
urban areas are making sizeable expenditures on schools and health
care because of their high concentration of illegal aliens. Federal
aid to these areas would be decreased if they were not counted,
Wilson said.
</TEXT>
