<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru   09-30 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0452,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Another Trafficker Will Be Extradited to U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with report that another trafficker will
be extradited to United States. TRIMS to tighten. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Ministry will extradite a
Colombian woman to Florida next week to face federal drug
trafficking charges there, the Bogota newspaper El Tiempo reported
today.
   The Associated Press could not immediately confirm the report
with the Justice Ministry, which was closed today.
   The drug trafficking suspect, Ana Helena Rodriguez, 37, was
handed the extradition notice Friday, and she has until Oct. 6 to
appeal, the newspaper said. She was arrested last month.
   Diane Cossin, spokeswoman for the U.S. Attorney's office in
Miami, said today that Ms. Rodriguez is one of several defendants
in a drug importation conspiracy case in Miami. She did not have
details of the charges.
   Ms. Rodriguez would become the second Colombian extradited to
the United States since President Virgilio Barco declared war on
drug traffickers Aug. 19.
   The first was Eduardo Martinez Romero, who was sent to Atlanta
Sept. 6 to face federal charges of money laundering.
   Neither is on a list compiled by the U.S. Justice Department of
12 most wanted Colombian traffickers being sought for extradition
to the United States.
   Seven bombs exploded Friday night in Colombia, five in Bogota
and two in the western city of Cali, the national police said in a
communique.
   Four of the bombs in Bogota were at public schools and one at a
bank, the police said. In Cali one bomb exploded at a department
store and another at a small grocery store near a Colombian air
force base, the police said.
   The seven bombs injured seven people slightly, including two
children at one of the Bogota schools, the police said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the bombs.
   The government's security forces have assumed that a wave of
bombings that began last month are the work of drug traffickers.
   There have been 125 bombs with 10 deaths and 148 people hurt. To
combat the wave of bombings, police have stepped up car searches at
Bogota checkpoints.
   On Friday, Barco made a speech at the United Nations in New York
calling for a worldwide effort to seize traffickers' assets.
   Drug barons began their offensive in response to a government
anti-drug crackdown announced hours after the leading presidential
candidate was assassinated by traffickers on Aug. 18. Sen. Luis
Carlos Galan had led a crusade against drugs in Medellin, the
nation's cocaine capital.
   Bogota Mayor Andres Pastrana said in a televised speech late
Thursday the army and police were stepping up security in the
capital to try to catch terrorists before they can deliver bombs.
   On Friday, security forces searched cars at various points in
the city of 6 million, then moved on to set up new checkpoints.
Pastrana said there would be up to 120 checkpoints at any given
time.
   In the last two weeks, with only a few checkpoints, Bogota
security forces have inspected 12,330 vehicles and have found 363
pounds of dynamite, 145 guns and 17,153 rounds of ammunition,
Pastrana said.
   In his speech to the 159-nation U.N. General Assembly, Barco
urged all nations to sign the Vienna Convention on narcotics
trafficking, which provides penalties for users such as seizure of
ships and confiscation of property.
   ``A new world war is being waged by an aggressor unrestrained by
the traditional rules of engagement or by the responsibilities of
national sovereignty,'' Barco told the world body. ``There must be
no safe haven for the narco-terrorists,'' he said to loud applause.
   Barco spoke under extraordinary security precautions that
included sharpshooters perched atop buildings, bomb-sniffing dogs
and a legion of U.N. police aided by bomb squads.
</TEXT>
