<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1034EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pope-Runcie     09-30 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope-Runcie,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paisley Threatens to Disrupt Runcie Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-papal activist threatened today to disrupt
the first visit to the Vatican by the Anglican church leader,
Archbishop Robert Runcie.
   The activist, the Rev. Ian Paisley, delivered a written protest
about Runcie's trip shortly after the Anglican leader held his
second meeting at the Vatican in two days with Pope John Paul II.
   ``If I spoil the party, I'll have done very well,'' Paisley told
reporters as he gave the protest to the archbishop's press
secretary at the English College residence for seminarians, where
Runcie is staying.
   Paisley is a Northern Ireland loyalist and head of the Free
Presbyterian Church in Northern Ireland, which is vehemently
anti-Roman Catholic.
   Paisley, who is also a member of the British and European
parliaments, refused to say what kinds of protests he planned
during Runcie's four-day visit, which ends Monday.
   Last year, Paisley interrupted a speech by Pope John Paul to the
European Parliament by screaming, ``I renounce you as the
anti-Christ.''
   Runcie, spiritual head of the state Church of England and leader
of the world's 70 million Anglicans, met for 55 minutes this
morning with the pope, head of 850 million Roman Catholics.
   They were expected to discuss efforts to reunite the churches
that split in the 16th century over the Vatican's refusal to annul
the marriage of Henry VIII and Catherine of Aragon.
   No details were released about the talks, which also involved
Runcie's advisers and members of the Pontifical Council for
Promoting Christian Unity.
   Later today, the pope and Runcie were to pray together at
vespers and deliver speeches touching on reunification efforts,
which have been troubled by the Anglican church's ordination of
women.
   In the letter to Runcie, made available to reporters, Paisley
said: ``Your endeavor to de-Protestantize the Church of England and
make it a mere annex of Rome strikes at the constitutional liberty
of the United Kingdom and is destructive to the integrity of the
throne, the position of the queen and the Protestant succession.''
   The letter accused Runcie of ``high treason'' for the Anglican
leader's recent remarks that the Church of England might recognize
papal authority in a united church.
   Runcie's statements on papal leadership echoed a view stated
several years ago by a Vatican-Anglican commission working on a
framework for church unity.
   Nonetheless, the comments drew fire from Evangelicals in the
Church of England, who base their teaching strictly on the Bible
and oppose unity with Rome.
   In a brief speech today, Runcie told John Paul he was wearing a
ring that was given by Pope Paul VI to Anglican Archbishop Michael
Ramsey in 1966. He described it as ``a sign not unlike an
engagement ring.''
   ``It is a token of commitment,'' Runcie said. ``I wear it today
as we rededicate ourselves to the search for visible and
sacramental unity between Anglicans and Roman Catholics throughout
the world.''
   In his brief remarks, the pontiff noted the progress in
Anglican-Catholic relations in recent years, but said: ``We must
face our differences honestly.''
   Runcie gave the pope a painting of St. Augustine landing in
Britain to convert the English in the 6th century. The pope
presented the Anglican leader with a reproduction of an 11th
century illuminated book of Benedictine prayers.
   Runcie follows his three predecessors in visiting the Vatican.
The first visit to Rome by an archbishop of Canterbury, the head of
Anglicans worldwide, occurred in 1960.
   Runcie and John Paul have met previously in Africa, India and
Assisi, Italy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
