<FIRST>r w AM-US-Singapore     09-30 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Singapore,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Looks to Step up Military Role in Singapore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has offered to step up
its military cooperation with the strategically located Asian
city-state of Singapore, Pentagon officials say.
   ``We've told them that we're prepared to send a small number of
fighter aircraft there on a temporary basis,'' said a high-level
Pentagon official who spoke on condition he not be identified by
name.
   Singapore, with a population of 2.6 million in an area about the
size of Chicago, is positioned on one of the world's most strategic
waterways, the Strait of Malacca, with access to both the Indian
Ocean and the South China Sea.
   The United States has strong economic ties with the increasingly
influential nation, which has a predominantly Chinese financial
center.
   The U.S. offer comes as the administration is preparing to enter
potentially difficult talks with the Philippines on extending the
lease of six U.S. military bases. The pact is due to expire in
September 1991.
   President Corazon Aquino said Thursday she has accepted
President Bush's offer to begin the talks, but she said there can
be no certainty the negotiations will produce agreement.
   Any agreement must be ratified by two-thirds of the 23-member
Senate, where opposition is strong. At least 12 senators have
called publicly for the bases to be closed, while others have
demanded that U.S. payments increase dramatically.
   Vice President Dan Quayle said during his visit there this past
week that he was confident the two sides would reach agreement and
guarantee the ``longtime involvement'' of the United States in the
Philippines.
   The Pentagon official stressed that the United States has no
interest in replacing its Philippine bases with those in Singapore,
primarily because the facilities there are limited by the size of
the tiny nation.
   About 40,000 American troops, civilian employees and military
dependents are stationed at the six U.S. Philippine installations,
including Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay naval base.
   ``Singapore would make available facilities on a military base
that is being vacated by New Zealand,'' the official said.
   The United States would use the facilities to position aircraft
there, make ship calls and do some repair work, the official said.
   It would involve ``a small number of people _ 100 or less,'' the
official said.
   The United States is aware that such a development is not
necessarily desired by Singapore's neighbors, Malaysia and
Indonesia, the official said.
   However, even the small amount of cooperation is expected to
please the Singapore government, the official said.
   ``It's really not as much as they would like,'' the official
said.
   Singapore said publicly over the summer that it was interested
in hosting the Americans.
   In June, a military survey team visited the island and submitted
a report to the Joint Chiefs of Staff and other agencies on the
feasibility of increased military cooperation.
   The two nations have a military agreement, allowing for U.S.
Navy ships to make port calls and Air Force planes to refuel. Some
joint military maneuvers have been held.
   Singapore has had a strong anti-communist heritage and is a
staunch regional supporter of free enterprise. Its 1987 per capita
income of $7,400 ranks it 19th in the world.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
