<FIRST>r i AM-India-Submarine     09-30 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Submarine,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Launches First Homemade Submarine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi
flipped an electric switch on Saturday and a 211-foot black
cylinder splashed into the sea, the first submarine built in India.
   The sub is a version of two other vessels built for India by the
West German firm Howaldtswerke Deutsche Weft. The first two were
built in Germany, but a contract called for Saturday's sub and one
more vessel to be built in India.
   Gandhi and his wife, Sonia, were among the dignitaries present.
The prime minister said ``technology must not only be borrowed. It
must also be improved and improvised lest we be saddled with
outdated equipment.''
   The $94 million vessel was named the Shalki, after a fish.
   The contract with the German firm has been steeped in
controversy. News reports have alleged that an Indian agent was
paid a $23 million kickback for the contract.
   Defense Minister V.P. Singh announced he had launched a probe
into alleaged kickbacks in defense contracts. Singh resigned from
the post April 12 after members of Gandhi's Congress Party accused
him of attempting to embarrass the government with the
investigations.
   Singh subsequently formed his own party and is now running for
the prime minister's post in general elections that must be held by
the end of the year.
</TEXT>
