<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica 3rdLd-Writethru a0489 09-30 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0489,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Allow Black Protests on Whites-Only Beaches</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with final crowd estimates, details. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>By SAHM VENTER</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of black and mixed-race
people picnicked and swam at whites-only beaches near Cape Town and
Port Elizabeth today as clergymen declared that God meant the sand
and water for everyone.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, wearing a yellow sun-hat with
the slogan, ``Free the Beaches,'' and a T-shirt saying, ``Just Call
Me Arch,'' confronted police who had initially ordered some of the
crowd of 1,500 to leave the beach in the conservative seaside town
of Strand, 20 miles east of Cape Town.
   Some families left during the discussion but most stayed,
opening their picnic lunches, swimming and wading in the water,
while 100 white people watched from the roadside. Police took no
action.
   ``I hope that the inhabitants of the Strand will realize that we
have liberated them,'' Tutu said. ``They don't have to watch
whether black people are walking on their beaches any longer. They
will enjoy the liberation of being able to share.''
   He said the black beachgoers were ``making sure they had staked
their claim properly. They walked around and wet their feet in
God's water.''
   About 1,000 people of all races gathered peacefully under heavy
police supervision in Port Elizabeth, in the eastern Cape province,
dancing and singing as a sign was erected declaring the end of
apartheid on Pollock Beach, reserved for whites for about 35 years.
   Seven buses brought black people from townships 10 miles north
of Port Elizabeth, where the City Council has asked that all
beaches under its jurisdiction be desegregated. The provincial
administrator, who is appointed by the National Party government,
has refused.
   Former Mayor Graham Richards erected the sign on a post in the
sand while a crowd gathered to hear prayers, speeches and poetry
readings. Other black and white beachgoers swam and sat in the sun.
   ``This mass non-racial picnic reminds us who we are, that we are
God's family. It is human selfishness and greed that makes beaches
for whites only,'' said the Rev. David Vika, of the
Interdenominational Ministers Association.
   The homemade sign, in black lettering on a white background, was
made to look like the nearby municipal posts which declare the
beach is for whites only. But the new sign said, ``We the people of
Port Elizabeth hereby declare Pollock Beach open for the use of all
people. By order.''
   A magistrate gave permission for the Port Elizabeth
demonstration, which was planned to last all day, but no approval
was sought for the protest at the Strand, and police initially
tried to stop the black and mixed-race families from getting to the
beach.
   Police pulled their vans up on the sand and gave the people a
few minutes to leave, then took foreign television crews and local
photographs away to a nearby police station, where they were set
free.
   Tutu told a news conference later he was afraid when police took
the journalists away they planned to use force against the crowd.
Tutu said that when thousands of blacks tried to get to the Strand
beach on Aug. 19 police used whips and dogs to drive them away.
   Police maintained a high profile, standing on the beach and
watching the crowds until the afternoon, but many began smiling,
and waved as they left, when the crowds thinned out, according to
the South African Press Association.
   On Friday, 20,000 anti-apartheid demonstrators marched in
southeastern King William's Town to protest apartheid and police
brutality. No violence was reported during the demonstration, which
received official permission.
</TEXT>
