<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Peace     09-30 1051</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Peace,1086</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon Peace Talks Face Major Obstacles</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>By ED BLANCHE</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lebanese lawmakers meeting in Saudi
Arabia seek to end more than 14 years of civil war in their
homeland, a task that has defeated would-be peacemakers since 1975.
   On the face of it, the meeting between Lebanon's Christian and
Moslem legislators appears to have as little chance of success as
earlier efforts to end a war in which more than 150,000 people have
been killed.
   The Maronite Catholics, the main Christian sect that has
dominated the government since independence from France in 1943,
say they will not agree to political reforms until there are
guarantees of a withdrawal by Syria's 40,000 troops in Lebanon.
   The Syrians, not party to the Saudi Arabian meeting but present
in spirit, say they will not pull out until the Christians share
power equally with the Damascus-backed Moslems.
   The Syrians entered Lebanon in 1976 under an Arab League mandate
to quell the civil war. They failed, but have used that
increasingly tattered mandate to justify staying in Lebanon.
   Even if the legislators meeting under Arab League auspices do
reach agreement, there are no guarantees that Lebanon's Christian
and Moslem warlords will heed any accord.
   To be sure, the initiative, the most intensive Arab effort so
far mounted to snuff out the civil war, has achieved a cease-fire
that halted six months of artillery battles between the Syrians and
Christian forces led by Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Many Lebanese are weary of a war that has dismembered their
country. But major obstacles that have been insurmountable in the
past remain. Key Lebanese leaders on both sides have criticized the
Arab League's peace plan.
   More significantly, there are the regional powers who have
repeatedly intervened in Lebanon, fanning the flames of war when it
suited their purposes.
   Syria, Israel, Iran, Iraq, Libya and the Palestinians have all
turned Lebanon into a proxy battleground for their feuds.
   It is this Gordian Knot of foreign meddling, as well as the deep
rooted hostility among Lebanon's militia leaders, that has stymied
the peacemakers in the past, leaving tiny Lebanon prey to the wider
strategies of more powerful states.
   Aoun, isolated and outnumbered, had little choice but to accept
the cease-fire, but believes there can be no peace while the
Syrians remain in Lebanon.
   He says he is prepared to make concessions but has pressured
Christian legislators to give nothing away until the Arab League
guarantees a Syrian withdrawal, something it has not been able to
do.
   Syrian President Hafez Assad, stubbornly determined to hold onto
Lebanon after a series of political setbacks that have undermined
his prestige, clearly stonewalled the Arab League into not making a
Syrian withdrawal an issue.
   ``It is glaringly obvious that the Arab League statement does
not even employ the word `withdrawal' in relation to future Syrian
troop movements,'' said Charles Snow, an analyst with the respected
Middle East Economic Survey.
   ``In this, as in virtually all its other proposals, the
initiative represents little more than an open-ended endorsement of
Syria's stated aims in Lebanon.''
   Syria, long the main power broker in Lebanon, considers its
neighbor to be vital to its strategic interests as a buffer on its
vulnerable western flank against Israel.
   Assad has also linked a withdrawal to a pullout by the Israelis,
who occupy a border strip in south Lebanon, and to the return of
the Golan Heights, captured by Israel in 1967 and later annexed.
   All efforts to persuade the Israelis to abandon these
territories have failed and there is nothing to indicate that
anything has changed.
   Iraq, Syria's archrival in the Arab world, has backed Aoun for
no other reason than to take revenge on Assad for supporting Iran
during the eight-year Iran-Iraq war and to bog down the Syrians in
the Lebanese quagmire.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's objective is nothing less than
undermining Assad's prestige in the Arab world and within Syria,
where he faces severe economic woes, to bring him down.
   ``Aoun's Iraqi backers are doubtless willing to fight to the
last Maronite in Lebanon'' to cripple Assad, Snow commented.
   Saudi Arabia, a member of the three-member Arab League committee
mediating to end the Lebanese carnage, could pressure Assad to back
off because it is the only Arab state still bankrolling radical
Syria.
   But the Saudis remain suspicious of Saddam's revived regional
ambitions following the Persian Gulf cease-fire and look to Syria
as a counterweight.
   Druse Moslem leader Walid Jumblatt has declared that the
proposed reforms do not go far enough in stripping the Maronites of
their traditional powers.
   ``The military battle is not yet over,'' he declared.
   Nabih Berri, leader of the Shiite Moslem Amal militia and a
major Syrian ally, also says the proposed reforms are ``not
enough'' because they envision splitting power equally between
Christians and Moslems.
   The 1.2 million-strong Shiites, long downtrodden but now
Lebanon's largest sect, demand the greatest share of power.
   Syria has used its alliance with Iran to put pressure on Aoun.
   Tehran and Damascus have publicly proclaimed solidarity. But
Syria is a secular socialist state that has ruthlessly crushed
Islamic fundamentalist dissidents who have much in common with
predominantly Shiite Iran.
   The Tehran Times daily, which often reflects the thinking of
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani, stressed that Syria must
``make sincere efforts ... to establish political justice'' in
Lebanon, a clear statement of support for the Shiites, or fighting
``with vaster dimensions'' would erupt again.
   ``The Syrians must admit that there is a difference between
fighting against Zionism and imperialism and occupying a
neighboring country,'' it declared.
   Rafsanjani, leader of Tehran's so-called pragmatists, apparently
hopes to restore Iran's relations with the West and appears to be
trying to rein in revolutionary radicals who back Shiite militants
in Lebanon holding most of 16 Western hostages.
   The Americans hope Rafsanjani's emergence will herald the
release of eight U.S. captives and don't want to antagonize Iran or
Syria, much to Aoun's chagrin.
   Rafsanjani is supported by some Lebanese Shiites. But the
hardliners holding the hostages remain loyal to Tehran's
anti-Western radicals, who could use them to keep Lebanon on the
boil to jeopardize Rafsanjani's efforts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ed Blanche is The AP's Middle East new editor, formerly based in
Beirut and now in Nicosia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
