<FIRST>r a AM-LastTemptation-Suit     09-30 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Last Temptation-Suit,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>$1 Million Suit Filed Over Pre-Emption of ``Last Temptation''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A local television viewer wants so badly to
see ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' he is suing a cable company
that decided not to show the controversial film.
   Felix H. Olim of suburban Midwest City filed suit Friday in
federal court here to force Multimedia Cablevision to show the film
on Cinemax when it is telecast for the rest of the country. He also
wants $1 million in damages.
   Multimedia announced Monday it would not telecast ``The Last
Temptation'' in Oklahoma, Kansas and North Carolina when it appears
on the premium channel.
   The suit says Multimedia ``infringed upon the religious rights
of its 90,000 subscribers'' by deciding to pre-empt the program.
   ``Whoever wishes not to view this or any transmission, always
has the option of choosing another channel, or turning off his
set,'' Olim said.
   Cinemax will broadcast the movie nationwide Monday and on four
other dates in October.
   The Oscar-nominated ``Last Temptation'' sparked national
protests when it was released 14 months ago because it portrayed
Jesus as confused over his identity and purpose and subject to
human desires.
   Meanwhile, Oklahoma State University regents postponed a showing
of the film by a student group on the Stillwater campus while they
attempted to decide if it is appropriate for a state-funded campus.
Plans for the showing had prompted at least threat of violence.
   An American Civil Liberties Union attorney said the group would
sue the university if the showing of the film is blocked, and Gov.
Henry Bellmon has told the regents it would be inappropriate to
censor the film.
   But state Rep. Bill Graves warned showing the film might violate
a 1910 Oklahoma law prohibiting blasphemy.
</TEXT>
