<FIRST>u i AM-VideoPirates     09-30 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Video Pirates,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filmmakers, Distributors Say Piracy Problem Improving</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for item slugged AM-Bat Pirates on the AM-News Advisory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Quicker than Robin could say ``Holy Copyright
Infringement, Batman!'' counterfeit copies of the smash movie
surfaced in Thailand's black markets.
   Although Japan and Hong Kong have cracked down on video piracy,
the rest of Asia remains the world's hub for such counterfeits,
copyright experts said Saturday at a seminar sponsored by the Third
Tokyo International Film Festival.
   Video piracy, the illegal taping of copyrighted videos, cost the
U.S. film industry $740 million last year.
   Copyright experts and government officials from Japan and Hong
Kong reported recent successes in controlling video piracy within
their borders.
   But China, where a video-cassette recorder costs 22 times an
average worker's annual income, is only now beginning to face the
problem, said Dai Qun, director of the Office of the Film Bureau.
China has 26,000 theaters where videotapes are shown to the public.
It also has 26,000 legitimate movie houses.
   In Thailand, video piracy is uncontrollable because copyright
laws are not enforced, said Lursak Thavornvanit, director of the
Thai Intellectual Property Protection Organization.
   ```Batman' appeared on the Thai black market just days after its
U.S. release,'' he told an audience of 400 video makers and
distributors.
   ``It's very difficult for anyone to do a legitimate business
because the pirates are so good and so efficient at managing the
market, and no one can afford to pay for the legitimate tapes,'' he
said.
   Pirated videos, which first appeared in 1983, have been
illegally duplicated or dubbed, either from legitimate copies or
from movie or television screens. They are sold or rented in video
stores at a fraction of the cost of legitimate copies or shown in
public places such as hotels and restaurants without payment to the
copyright owners, usually the films' producers.
   In Tokyo, a legitimate video tape rents for about $7, while a
pirated copy costs about $2. Nevertheless, Japan's video watchdog
group says the number of shops offering pirated videos has
plummeted in the last two years.
   Between 60 percent and 70 percent of the 12,000 video stores in
Japan sold pirated videos in 1987, but that number has declined to
30 percent, mostly because of tougher enforcement of copyright laws
and a beefed-up law that makes it illegal to possess pirated tapes,
said Tomohiro Tohyama, legal director of the Japan Federation
Against Copyright Theft.
   The criminal penalties under the revised Copyright Law are
imprisonment for up to three years or a $7,200 fine, but no
violators have ever gone to jail.
   Still, Tohyama thinks the law has been effective. ``It is almost
impossible to find a shop these days stocked 100 percent with
pirated videos. That wasn't true two years ago.''
   Tohyama said his organization's main goal _ to halt all home
taping of videos _ could take as long as 20 years. ``The Japanese
public simply doesn't understand copying videos is stealing, even
though it is intangible property.''
   American movies are popular fare in Japan, the U.S. film
industry's largest export target. Last year, almost three times as
many U.S. films were shown as Japanese films, according to the
Motion Picture Association of America.
   The top four grossing films in Japanese history are ``ET,''
``Star Wars,'' ``Jaws,'' and ``Ghostbusters,'' according to
industry statistics.
   Elsewhere in Asia ``Rambo'' can be seen in isolationist Burma,
and ``The Last Emperor'' was widely shown in China.
   Some South Korean filmmakers are so threatened by the weighty
competition of American movies that they allegedly ordered the
release of snakes and tear gas into theaters showing U.S. films.
   Videotapes of such U.S. blockbusters a ``Rambo,'' smuggled in by
boat through Vietnam's long coastline, are popular black market
items there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890930-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Poland Bjt   09-30 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Emphasizing Multination Approach on Economic Aid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Notwithstanding charges it is being too timid,
the Bush administration is resisting calls for the United States to
directly spend billions of dollars to aid Poland's historic attempt
to transform its economy from communism to capitalism.
   It's not that President Bush doesn't want the Poles to succeed.
   In an address last week to the 152-nation International Monetary
Fund and its sister organization, the World Bank, Bush hailed
developments in Eastern Europe as ``stunning.''
   ``There is no greater opportunity before us all today than the
challenge of Poland,'' he said.
   ``We must do more,'' he said.
   On the other hand, Bush mentioned no specific figure for U.S.
aid beyond the $219 million already announced.
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., called the president's proposal
``pathetically timid'' and Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, said the ``administration's timidity ... is puzzling and
dismaying.''
   ``Bush is saying he wants to provide assistance to a newly
reformed system, but the bottom line is, `Where's the beef? Where
is the money?''' said Joseph Pelzman, professor of economics at
George Washington University.
   The president reportedly is considering additional U.S. aid, but
the administration seems inclined to channel most Western help
through the IMF and World Bank.
   The key word in Bush's speech last week was ``we.'' He was
speaking to the world, not just to Americans.
   ``The United States might kick in some more food aid from time
to time and put aside some scholarships, but in terms of cash aid,
it's going to work through the World Bank and IMF,'' said economics
professor Howard Wachtel of American University.
   A Treasury official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Friday, ``The Bush administration believes that the World Bank and
IMF have particularly important roles to play in supporting
economic reform in Poland, both through policy advice and financial
support.''
   Academic experts on the subject say there are a number of
advantages to this approach, both political and budgetary.
   ``It is a way to provide burden sharing and there is nothing
wrong with that,'' Pelzman said.
   Western European democracies have as much, if not more, reason
than the United States to help Poland succeed.
   Another advantage lies in the technicalities of how the IMF
raises its money. The fund assesses each member a quota, which the
countries supply from their reserves. The quota can be withdrawn on
demand, so it doesn't count as spending for U.S. budget purposes.
   Additional direct U.S. aid, unlike an increase in IMF quotas,
would mean the administration and Congress would have to cut
elsewhere to meet the requirements of the Gramm-Rudman deficit
reduction law.
   Indeed, IMF officials, who are seeking agreement by the end of
the year to double the fund's resources from $120 billion to $240
billion, are hoping U.S. desire to aid Eastern Europe will help
persuade the United States to accede to a substantial quota
increase.
   But, perhaps the most important factors in the administration's
thinking are political, both international and domestic.
   If the United States charges too strongly into Poland, it could
rattle the Soviet Union, already nervous about the Solidarity-led
government that took office Aug. 24.
   Also, Polish officials are beginning what at least initially
will be a jarring reform program causing widespread unemployment
and other disruptions as inefficient state-run enterprises are
forced to operate in a competitive system for the first time.
   The IMF, in exchange for its assistance, normally insists that
countries follow through on promised reforms. It acts as sort of an
international enforcer. That's in line with what the United States
wants, but the administration is not eager for the flak that
accompanies the tough cop role.
   One of the reasons Congress is so keen on aiding Poland is the
millions of Americans of Polish descent who closely watch
conditions in their native land.
   Having the IMF take the lead ``gives the United States political
cover. It puts the IMF out front. They take the flak if there are
criticisms to be taken,'' Wachtel said.
   ``You don't want to make the Americans look as if they are the
ones making the (Polish) population eat less,'' added Pelzman.
   But there's a danger in relying too much on international
organizations more accustomed to dealing with Third World countries
with underdeveloped free enterprise systems than with centrally
planned economies operating with no experience in free markets,
Wachtel said.
   ``The IMF and World Bank can make some very big mistakes if they
simply parachute in their standard program where it's not suited,''
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
