<FIRST>u i AM-Ukraine     09-30 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ukraine,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Ukraine Party Leader Pledges to Get Republic Moving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new head of the nation's second-largest
republic pledged in an interview published Saturday to attack acute
housing and food shortages that built up during the 17-year rule of
his conservative predecessor.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda also printed an interview with
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev in which he gave lukewarm thanks to
outgoing Ukrainian leader and conservative Politburo member
Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky, indicating the differences that colored
the men's relationship.
   ``The tempo of renewal in various spheres of life in the
republic ... is clearly insufficient,'' new party leader Vladimir
A. Ivashko told Pravda in his first published comments since being
chosen Thursday to replace Shcherbitsky.
   ``The people are very dissatisfied,'' said the new chief of the
republic that is home to 50 million people, the Soviet breadbasket
and an important coal-producing and industrial area.
   He ticked off a half-dozen priorities that included improved
housing, food supplies, consumer goods, health care, the
environment and nuclear energy problems linked to the Chernobyl
nuclear power accident in 1986 and the construction of another
nuclear plant in the Crimea.
   Ivashko also pledged to allow the full development of Ukrainian
culture, a sign he is likely to be more inclined toward compromise
with those who are pushing for preservation of the Ukrainian
language and demanding more economic and political autonomy.
   The Ivashko, 56, seen as a supporter of Gorbachev's reforms,
said one of his main tasks will be to work out a program of the
Ukraine's economic independence within the framework of the Soviet
economy.
   Shcherbitsky, 71, the last Politburo holdover from the regime of
President Leonid I. Brezhnev, was intolerant of dissident.
   However, under Gorbachev's reform policy, Ukrainians began
making the same demands as other ethnic activists in the Soviet
Union, and in early September they held the founding meeting of the
Rukh political movement. The grassroots political movement
professes support for Gorbachev's reforms but that in some cases
goes further in demanding democratic reforms and local control.
   Echoing Gorbachev, Ivashko said one of his most important tasks
would be to strengthen the party so that it does not lose
initiative at a time when many informal political groups are
placing demands before it and the government.
   There had been many reports in the past several years that
Shcherbitsky was being forced out by Gorbachev, but he held on to
his job until he and two other Politburo members were eased out of
the country's ruling body on Sept. 20. Ukrainian party leaders
chose Ivashko in secret balloting on Sept. 28.
   In rather brief remarks about Shcherbitsky, Gorbachev told
Pravda the retired leader's many years of party work ``deserved a
high evaluation.''
   Gorbachev, who took part in the Ukrainian party meeting at which
Shcherbitsky retired, said party leaders praised the former leader
``as a person who worked very hard, and was not satisfied with what
was achieved.''
   Gorbachev indicated that Shcherbitsky's age and health were
among the reasons he was relieved.
   Shcherbitsky told Pravda that Ivashko had all the necessary
qualities to run the Ukraine and that he would justify the trust of
party leaders.
</TEXT>
