<DOCNO> AP890930-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1305EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon Bjt   09-30 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, Bjt,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speaker Tells Lebanese Lawmakers They Must Find Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIF, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The speaker of Lebanon's splintered
parliament told the assembly Saturday that they have no choice but
to find a way to end their nation's 14-year cycle of bloodshed.
   Christian and Moslem lawmakers, gathered in this mountain resort
for their first meeting in more than a year, are divided over the
presence of Syrian troops backing Moslem forces in Lebanon and
Moslem demands for greater power.
   Speaker Hassan Husseini, a Shiite Moslem, told the deputies that
failure to resolve their differences would mean ``a total loss of
hope'' in the devastated country, where fighting has been halted by
a fragile truce.
   ``We have no choice but to succeed,'' he told the
parliamentarians.
   King Fahd, in an opening address read by Foreign Minister Prince
Saud al Faisal in Taif's Conference Palace, called on the feuding
Christian and Moslem parliamentarians to cooperate in finding a
settlement to the conflict in which more than 150,000 people have
been killed since 1975.
   ``Now that the situation has shifted from the arena of warriors
to the negotiators' table, it is high time we moved from trading
artillery shells and accusations to hasten the peacemaking,'' the
king's message said.
   The Saudi monarch said Lebanese must rule their own nation.
   Most of Lebanon, except an 320-square mile Christian enclave
north of Beirut, is under the control of Syria, which has 40,000
troops in Lebanon. Israel occupies a ``security zone'' of Lebanese
territory along its border.
   Fahd is a member of a three-nation committee mandated by the
22-member Arab League to bring peace and reconcile Lebanon's
feuding factions.
   Fahd, King Hassan II of Morocco and President Chadli Bendjedid
of Algeria formulated a seven-point peace plan that calls for
political reforms which the Lebanese parliamentarians will debate.
   The Taif meeting, the first by Lebanon's parliament outside the
country, was designed to reduce sectarian pressures on the
legislators that have been a major factor in the collapse of
earlier initiatives.
   Lebanese deputies who arrived in Taif late Friday said the
meeting would last from three to 10 days.
   Before the deputies left Beirut Friday, Lebanon's Moslem
government leader, Moslem Salim Hoss, said the Taif meeting ``could
be the last chance for peace in Lebanon.''
   Conference sources said 63 of Lebanon's 73 surviving legislators
_ 33 Christians and 30 Moslems _ were in Taif in Saudi Arabia's
western mountains.
   Three Shiite Moslem and seven Christian deputies failed to show
up. ``No one has refused to come, but some gave medical reasons for
not attending,'' Saud said.
   Twenty-five of the deputies in the 99-seat parliament have been
killed or died of natural causes since the last general election in
1972. The fighting has prevented elections since then.
   A cease-fire in Lebanon took effect a week ago, halting six
months of fierce artillery battles between the Syrian Army, which
backs the Moslems, and Christian forces led by Gen. Michel Aoun.
   More than 900 people were killed and nearly 3,000 wounded in the
fighting that included some of the most ferocious bombardments of
the war. Most of the casualties were civilians.
   The cease-fire, and the lifting of blockades by both sides, was
the first phase of the ambitious, seven-point Arab League peace
plan.
   It envisages political reforms that will give Lebanon's Moslem
majority equal power with the Christians, led by Maronites, who,
under an unwritten agreement, have dominated the government,
parliament, judiciary and army since independence from France in
1943.
   The plan also proposed increasing the number of seats in
Lebanon's parliament to 128, divided equally among Christians and
Moslems. Since independence, the Christians have had a 6-5 edge in
the House.
   In 1943, the Christians were considered the majority. But
estimates now give Moslems at least 55 percent of Lebanon's 4
million people.
   The peace plan also proposes a Syrian pullback from Moslem areas
of Beirut to the Bekaa Valley in east Lebanon within two years
provided political agreement can be reached. Complete withdrawal
would follow a security pact between Syria and Lebanon.
   Some Christian legislators, pressed by Aoun, have said they will
not discuss political reforms until Syria agrees to a timetable for
a complete withdrawal.
   Syria has its troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate. Aoun claims the Syrians have abrogated that
mandate by siding with the Moslems.
   Syria considers Lebanon, its western neighbor, vital to its
security.
   The peace plan envisages the Lebanese legislators electing a new
president to replace Amin Gemayel, a Maronite whose six-year term
expired Sept. 22, 1988.
   In the dying minutes of his presidency, Gemayel appointed Aoun
to head a caretaker military government. By naming a Maronite as
premier, Gemayel broke the unwritten covenant under which the
president is a Maronite, the premier a Sunni Moslem and the
parliament speaker a Shiite.
   Moslems rejected Aoun's appointment and supported the
Syrian-backed cabinet led by Hoss, a Sunni Moslem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
