<FIRST>u a PM-Hugo-AtlantaDoctors 2ndLd-Writethru a0537 09-30 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Atlanta Doctors, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0537,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Doctor Says Red Tape Imperils Mercy Mission to St. Croix</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with doctor saying red tape has
delayed trip. Picks up 4th graf, `Osborne said Friday...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Atlanta physicians organized supplies
for a three-day mercy mission to St. Croix for the victims of
Hurricane Hugo, but said today that red tape held up their flight
to the Caribbean.
   ``We heard there were no medicines, and people were going into
comas,'' said Dr. William Osborne, medical director of Southside
Health Care Center, which is sending the team. ``So we volunteered
to go.''
   He said military officials in Washington and Puerto Rico were
trying to track down what happened to the military plane Osborne
thought he had arranged to carry the eight doctors, two nurses, a
respiratory therapist, a pharmacist and a social worker to St.
Croix.
   ``We're just trying to do something that's right and we're being
held up by all this red tape,'' he said. ``There's a possibility we
may not go if we can't get the plane this weekend. Some people have
other commitments.''
   Earlier today, Osborne said he thought bad weather in Atlanta
was delaying the military jet's arrival.
   He said if the medical team can't leave this weekend, he may
spend the week gathering more supplies and go next weekend to St.
Croix, where Hugo's fury killed four people and left most of the
island's 55,000 residents homeless, hungry and desperate.
   Osborne said Friday that the group had been planning the trip
since Monday. They expect to spend three days treating patients and
assessing the island's medical needs.
   ``If we do deem there is more need, we can come back and rally
the entire black community to assist in the efforts, with the
intention of returning at a later date,'' Osborne said. ``That is
our hope.''
   Kim Butler, a social worker at an Atlanta hospital and a native
of St. Croix, worked out details with civil defense officials in
Miami, who put her in touch with officials in St. Croix.
   The Southside staff spent Monday and Tuesday bundling up several
boxes of antibiotics, antiseptics, insulin, syringes, bandages and
gloves, and shipped the package off to St. Croix Wednesday.
   The team will take more supplies with them, including tetanus
immunizations and medication for heart and blood pressure
conditions, Osborne said.
   The group chose to go to St. Croix because members saw a greater
need there than in South Carolina, which also was raked by Hugo's
desructive winds.
   ``We felt enough people were helping in Charleston,'' Osborne
said. ``This island was totally devastated.''
</TEXT>
