<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1519EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo Bjt   09-30 1003</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo, Bjt,1033</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Storm Brews over Federal Response</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 5th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CHT1, CHT2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT DVORCHAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faye Thompson went to a federal aid
center Saturday for a loan to rebuild her auto repair shop and
patch the roof of her house torn open by Hurricane Hugo. What she
got was an application and instructions to come back Oct. 12 to
fill out forms.
   ``My house won't be standing by Oct. 12,'' said Mrs. Thompson,
42, as a steady drizzle fell. ``I need help right now. There's too
much red tape. What good is this piece of paper going to do for my
roof?''
   Nine days after Hurricane Hugo passed, a political storm still
rages over how quickly the federal government responded to a crisis
in South Carolina, where damage has been estimated at $3 billion or
more.
   The anger has focused on the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, which reports directly to the president and has a budget of
$600 million a year.
   A chief critic has been Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., who has
accused the agency of strangling aid attempts in red tape and has
called FEMA's hierarchy a ``bunch of bureaucratic jackasses'' who
would do best to ``get the hell out of the way.''
   President Bush, who flew to South Carolina on Friday for a brief
look at the damage, defended the administration's response to the
disaster, saying he was ``satisfied the federal government has
moved, and moved expeditiously.''
   Charleston Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr., a Democrat, accuses the
agency of being slow to respond.
   ``The system is not designed to cope immediately and urgently
with a major disaster,'' he said. ``They didn't bring in enough
people, enough resources.''
   As one example, he said FEMA officials asked for a written
assessment of the need for portable generators, even though
everybody knew of widespread power outages.
   FEMA already was in the Caribbean attempting to assist victims
of Hugo as the storm roared toward the mainland, spreading the
agency a bit thin.
   Hugo killed 33 people in the Caribbean; 28 deaths on the U.S.
mainland are blamed on the hurricane and its remnants.
   In South Carolina, some 50,000 people were displaced by the
storm, 270,000 lost jobs, and at least 135,000 still had no
electricity Saturday.
   Gov. Carroll Campbell warned that the state must build 65 miles
of protective sand dunes to prevent further damage to the
coastline. The tide is expected to rise to 2 feet higher than usual
in mid-October, a once-in-a-decade high because the moon will be
unusually close to the earth. The tide could further erode beaches.
   The governor said he discussed the ``mind-boggling'' dune
project with Bush. Federal funds would cover three-fourths of the
$65 million needed for the project.
   Campbell requested federal disaster aid the day after Hugo
struck the state Sept. 21. A FEMA representative in Charleston took
an aerial survey of the coast and Bush signed the disaster
declaration before noon the same day.
   But the first FEMA office didn't open until Thursday, a week
after Hugo battered the region. One of the first five FEMA centers
is located in a former toy store and was opened before electrical
power was restored. Five more open this weekend.
   FEMA spokesman Bill McAda said the agency waits at least four
days before it opens aid offices to give victims time to contact
their insurance agents.
   The centers help people get grants for repairs to homes or
businesses and aid for those who lost jobs to the storm. Assistance
also can be given on tax questions, insurance claims and price
gouging.
   Under one program, FEMA reimburses individuals and families who
qualify for temporary housing for up to two years. Those who don't
qualify under that program can apply for up to $10,000 in grants.
   Those who need immediate help with food, clothing and shelter
are directed to the American Red Cross.
   Residents looking for help are disheartened to find that jobless
pay may take two to three weeks to process, and they may not
actually receive their loans for two months.
   ``We're doing the best we can,'' said FEMA manager Shirley
Caraway. ``I feel for the people, but this process is necessary.
It's something they have to go through. It's their tax dollars.''
   Local officials gave the federal agency mixed reviews.
   Richard Wern, mayor of St. George in the hard-hit rural county
northwest of Charleston, said he had no contact with FEMA and no
nearby aid center, though hundreds of people were waiting in line
in his town for food and water.
   ``They need money to repair their water systems and their
wells,'' he said. ``That would help them become more
self-sufficient more quickly.''
   But in coastal Georgetown, city administrator Mitch Sizemore
said FEMA's help in paying for repairs to the municipal power
system ``is going to be tremendous.''
   Sizemore said some of the disappointment in FEMA may be based on
unrealistic expectations among elected officials unfamiliar with
the agency's mission, calling it a ``reimbursement agency'' that
moves in after the initial response by local governments.
   Riley said the federal government should cross-train employees
in all departments to handle emergencies so thousands of workers
could be shipped to disaster areas to process requests. FEMA has
350 people in South Carolina handling claims.
   Gregg Chappell, whose department oversees FEMA's disaster
assistance program, admitted the scope of Hugo's destruction
overwhelmed the agency.
   ``We need to deal with this type of disaster, this huge
disaster, differently than we do the normal disaster,'' he told
CNN's ``Newsmaker Saturday.''
   But the concession meant little to Ron Gibson, who has been
living out of one suitcase since his house and clothing shop on
Sullivan's Island was badly damaged in the storm.
   ``I haven't been able to work. I sit in the dark in frustration
and stand in these long lines,'' Gibson said. ``There has to be a
better setup. If it means expediting things quickly and settling up
later, do it.''
</TEXT>
