<FIRST>u i AM-Italy-Volcano     09-30 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Volcano,0138</SECOND>
<UNK>Lava Pours From Europe's Most Active Volcano</UNK>
<DATELINE>CATANIA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fountains of lava spewed Saturday from a
new crater on Mount Etna and sent a red-hot river of magma flowing
down the eastern slope of Europe's most active volanco.
   Scientists said the magma gushed from a 500-foot crater that
opened 8,500 feet up the mountain after a series of tremors on
Thursday.
   News reports said the river of lava was 15 yards wide and had
snaked down to the 4,500-foot level, still oozing forward at about
10 yards an hour.
   Mount Etna began its latest eruption on Sept. 11. Volcano
experts say there is no danger to any of the hamlets near the
mountain, which are protected by a series of peaks and valleys that
would channel the lava away from them.
</TEXT>
