<FIRST>r i AM-Ecuador-Colombia     09-30 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ecuador-Colombia,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ecuador Captures Important Colombian Drug Trafficker ^With AM-Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Colombian cocaine trafficker wanted
in the United States has been arrested in Ecuador and may be
extradited to Colombia within a few days, a senior government
official said Saturday.
   Evaristo Porras Ardila, regarded as a leader of the Medellin
drug cartel, was detained Thursday in Tulcan, a town on the
Colombian border, and turned over to Ecuador's drug police force,
the official said.
   ``We are going to extradite him to Colombia after the
investigation is completed,'' said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   A spokesman for the Colombian Embassy said the United States
wants to extradite Porras Ardila and try him on unspecified drug
trafficking charges.
   But Porras Ardila's name is not on a list the U.S. Justice
Department compiled of the top 12 most Colombian traffickers being
sought by U.S. courts, and no information was immediately available
on charges pending against him.
   Another Colombian official, who also demanded anonymity,
described Porras Ardila as one of Colombia's ``eight most
important'' narcotics traffickers. He is said to have his base in
Leticia in Colombia's Amazon jungle region.
   Porras Ardila has been linked with the assassination of
Guillermo Cano, director of the Colombian newspaper El Espectador,
sources said. He has been arrested twice in Colombia but was
released by judges both times.
   Tulcan, the Ecuadorean town where Porras Ardila was arrested
Thursday, is 90 miles northeast of Quito.
   Earlier this month, Ecuador extradited to Colombia two drug
traffickers who entered the country illegally in a small plane with
$300,000 in cash.
   For the last two years Colombian drug cartels have increased
their presence in Ecuador, a small nation of 10 million people,
making it an important trans-shipment point for cocaine smuggled to
the United States and Europe.
   President Virgilio Barco of Colombia ordered a crackdown on the
drug cartels in his country after Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, a leading
presidential candidate and outspoken foe of drug trafficking, was
assassinated Aug. 18.
   The traffickers responded by declaring war on the government,
and they said in a communique earlier this month that they would
prefer a grave in Colombia to a jail cell in the United States. The
top traffickers sought by the United States are believed to have
fled Colombia to evade arrest.
</TEXT>
