<DOCNO> AP890930-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1611EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-PEN     09-30 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-PEN,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>PEN Plans More East-West Contacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PEN international writers association plans
to increase its East-West contacts to take advantage of easing
political tensions brought about mainly by the Soviet Union's
political reforms.
   ``We have the feeling that we have now a historical moment,''
Alexander Blokh, PEN's international secretary, said at the
conclusion Friday of the organization's 54th World Congress.
   He said writers from Western and Eastern European nations ``now
can meet across what was yesterday the `Iron Curtain' in full
confidence, in full friendship.''
   The next PEN World Congress will be held in November 1991 in
Vienna, Austria. Before that the association plans to arrange
regular meetings in Vienna so that writers from the East and West
can exchange information they might have missed during the past 40
years of limited contacts.
   ``There might be new misunderstandings. We have lived very
different lives,'' Blokh said. ``We think we should use this
magnificent opportunity to get to understand each other in depth.''
   A Soviet Russian chapter based in Moscow was admitted to PEN in
May, ending a 65-year division with Moscow, and it sent delegates
to the Canadian congress.
   A second Soviet chapter, for Ukrainian writers and based in
Kiev, was accepted during last week's congress. Separate Czech and
Slovak chapters also were recognized.
   PEN, the International Association of Poets, Playwrights,
Editors, Essayists and Novelists, was founded in London in 1921 and
now has some 11,000 members in 95 chapters.
   But while optimism was expressed about Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness, there also were words
of caution.
   Czechoslovak playwright Vaclav Havel, denied a passport by his
government to attend the congress, sent a message asking PEN to
care for ``the frail foundations of our reawakened Czech and Slovak
centers.''
   Havel also asked the association's members to ``hope with us
that the Czechoslovak authorities, who have so far approved, will
not change their mind'' about the PEN chapters.
   The association's Writers in Prison Committee reported that the
number of cases on its list has reached a five-year high.
   ``It is a tendency that is very dangerous and unhappy,'' Swedish
publisher Thomas von Vegesack, the committee chairman, said Friday.
   He said that in May 1987, just before the glasnost campaign
started, the continent with the most cases of jailed writers was
Europe but most new cases now are in the Far East.
   Von Vegesack said 78 releases and 127 new arrests have been
reported since March, bringing the number of cases to 358.
   He also said the committee's most recent information from China
was 33 new cases of writers imprisoned since the pro-democracy
demonstrations in June.
   Blokh called the absence of delegates from the three Chinese PEN
chapters ``the great sadness'' of the convention.
   A resolution called on the Chinese government ``to cease the
persecution of writers, intellectuals and others, to prohibit the
use of torture and ensure that current detainees are treated
humanely, to guarantee the internationally recognied right to
freedom of expression for all citizens, and to release immediately
and unconditionally those who have been imprisoned for exercising
that right.''
   The Canadian English-speaking PEN chapter hosted the congress in
Toronto until Wednesday when delegates moved to Montreal where the
French-speaking chapter served as host.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
