<FIRST>r a AM-AppleSales     09-30 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apple Sales,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Industry Bailout Defended Despite Record Gross</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington apple growers grossed an
estimated record $493.6 million in the past year despite the scare
over the chemical Alar, calling into question the $9.5 million
federal bailout of the industry.
   But industry leaders said the gross sales do not tell the full
story because wholesale prices to farmers often lagged below the
cost of production.
   Still, news of the record sales _ counting the $9.5 of the
bailout itself _ was a surprise to staff members of the Washington
congressional delegation who sought the bailout.
   The previous record was $488 million in 1986.
   ``That's the first we've heard they had a banner year,'' said
Gretchen White, a staff member for U.S. Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash.,
who represents the nation's largest apple-growing region in central
Washington.
   U.S. Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., who also pursued the bailout,
plans to study the sales figures, said Doug Levy, deputy press
secretary.
   ``He feels very strongly that the right thing was done,'' Levy
said. ``There was no question a crisis followed the Alar scare.''
   Levy pointed out that the $9.5 million came from existing
federal funds kept in reserve to stabilize troubled agriculture
industries. The money comes from duties on foreign imports.
   The $493.6 million estimate was based primarily on marketing
figures reported in July, before the bailout payment was made, said
Mary Beth Lang, spokeswoman for the Washington Department of
Agriculture. However, it includes estimates of apples sales for the
final portion of the crop year ending in September, including those
apples sold through the buyout.
   Washington producers received about $9.1 million of the buyout,
with the rest going to growers in Michigan, New York and elsewhere
in the country, Ms. Lang said.
   She noted the department's January forecast had estimated a crop
worth $588 million, and said the Alar scare contributed to the
lower figure six months later.
   Washington produced the second-largest apple crop in its history
last year, about 65 million 42-pound boxes, and wholesale prices
were below the cost of production during much of the second half of
the year.
   ``We have been expanding production and have expanded cost
factors,'' said Chris Schlect, head of the Northwest Horticultural
Council, an organization of Washington and Oregon tree fruit
growers that lobbies Congress.
   He said that makes it inaccurate to look at raw sales figures
and make year-by-year comparisons.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture in August authorized the $9.5
million emergency purchase of apples stockpiled in warehouses in
six states. Under the program, warehouses diverted the fruit to the
poor or to charitable organizations and were paid.
   At the time, warehouses were bulging with record inventories of
fruit after summer sales slumped in the wake of the Alar scare.
   That controversy began in late February when a private consumer
group said eating apples treated with the growth regulator
increased cancer risk in children.
   The apple industry and federal Environmental Protection Agency
and the Food and Drug Administration disputed the report as an
exaggeration of the risk, but sales dropped. The EPA has proposed
new standards for use of the chemical.
   Industry officials argued they would not be able to sell the
stockpiled apples through normal channels in time to clear
warehouses for the 1989 crop, which is being harvested now.
   Schlect defended the program, saying it stablized the industry
and set up the prospect of a better 1989-1990 crop season.
   In terms of gross sales, apple growers made 42 percent more from
the 1988 crop than from the weather-plagued 1987 crop, which was
still the largest in history. The 1989 crop currently being
harvested is estimated to be the largest fresh-market crop in state
history at 75 million boxes. Washington will grow an estimated 60
percent of the nation's apples this year.
</TEXT>
