<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1646EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     09-30 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHUA, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 50 years ago, Edith Spargo picked
Leatrice Roy's name on a pen pal list secretly hoping Leatrice was
a boy's name.
   Even though Spargo was wrong, the friendship endured and the two
kept writing. They say they have no idea how many letters they
traded _ neither saved the letters, saying they didn't tell of
extraordinary events.
   For the first time in 45 years, they talked to each other in
person last week at Roy's home in a reunion that fanned memories
and brought tears.
   The correspondence began through a school program in October
1938. In her sixth-grade class in Belmont, N.C., Edith, then 12,
picked Leatrice's name from a list in a school newspaper.
   In her first letter, Spargo said, her first question was a
gender inquiry.
   If she was disappointed that Leatrice was a girl, the feeling
didn't last. Almost 51 years later, she still writes at least once
a month.
   ``It's just natural because we've done it so long,'' said
Spargo, 63, of Asheboro, N.C.
   Roy, 65, said she doesn't remember how her name got on the pen
pal list in North Carolina. When the two began writing, she was 14
and a pupil at Spring Street Junior High School.
   When the Spargos arrived last week, it was the first time the
women had seen each other since the July 4 weekend of 1944. At that
time, Spargo, then 18 and living in New Jersey with her husband,
came up to New Hampshire. Roy was 20 and not yet married.
   ``We cried,'' Roy said, her eyes filling again. ``I couldn't
believe it was happening. I couldn't believe finally we were
getting together.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chilly Chuggers, Jumbo Burps and Double Gulps
are the contenders in a soda battle that convenience stores are
hoping consumers won't find hard to swallow.
   The Starvin' Marvin chain sells the 32-ounce Chilly Chugger and
at High's stores, customers are offered the 46-ounce Jumbo Burp.
Seven-Eleven, however, is the leader with the mammoth 64-ounce
Double Gulp.
   Even fast-food giant McDonald's has recognized the move toward
gluttony and introduced its Super-Size 32-ounce soft drinks.
   ``Convenience stores have been trying to widen their customer
base and the easiest way to do that is to get more out of the
customers you have,'' said Donna Lawrence, a spokeswoman for the
National Association of Convenience Stores in Alexandria, Va.
   While fountain drinks account for only 2.8 percent of sales at
convenience stores, they carry a 64 percent gross profit margin.
   Seven-Eleven introduced its 64-ounce serve-yourself Double Gulp
nationwide this summer. Even 7-Eleven officials aren't sure why
anyone would want to drink a half-gallon of soda, which is the
equivalent of more than five 12-ounce cans.
   ``It's an odd product,'' said Steve Barnickel, owner of a
Baltimore 7-Eleven franchise. ``It's just something we have in case
someone wants to buy it. ... I think it's too much soda.''
</TEXT>
