<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     09-30 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body of 19th Century General Returned to Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of Gen. Juan Manuel de
Rosas, whose 19th century rule left political anomosities that are
still present, was returned from France Saturday in a move to heal
today's divisions.
   The casket, wrapped in the blue and white Argentine flag and
with a red poncho and a cavalry saber on top, arrived aboard an air
force plane from Paris and was flown by helicopter to Rosario, 188
miles north of Buenos Aires.
   ``We cannot construct a true fatherland atop hatred between
brothers,'' President Carlos Menem said in a televised speech at a
Rosario monument marking the spot the Argentine flag first flew in
1812.
   Rosas, who exercised iron rule over a confederation of newly
independent and rebellious provinces from 1835 until his ouster and
exile in 1852, is considered a hero by nationalists and a tyrant by
liberals.
   ``In welcoming Rosas we are saying goodbye to an old, wornout,
anachronistic and absurd country, a country of failure, hatred and
false illusions,'' said Menem, who took office on July 8.
   Standing beside the president were some of Rosas' descendants,
government officials, Roman Catholic church leaders and military
officers.
   Menem said he was ``willing to pay all the political costs ...
so that we can join hands, open our hearts and put resentments
behind us.''
   Argentines are bitterly divided over Menem's announced plan to
pardon military officers accused of human rights abuses during the
campaign against leftists by military juntas that ruled Argenina
from 1976 to 1983.
   At least 8,900 people disappeared during the violent suppression
and it is believed virtually all of them were killed.
   Menem denied published reports that he would use the ceremonies
honoring Rosas to declare the pardons.
   ``That's not among my plans,'' he told a Buenos Aires radio
station. ``I already said (the pardons would be ordered) before the
end of the year, perhaps before the end of the month. I'm talking
about October, not September.''
   The pardons are fiercely opposed by human rights groups, who
accuse the former military rulers of genocide. Those groups, some
leftist political parties and a faction of Menem's Peronist Party,
launched a campaign Friday to obtain a million signatures opposing
any presidential pardon.
   Menem is expected to announce pardons for some or all of the 18
generals and admirals facing trial on charges of human rights
violations.
   Rosas, a wealthy landowner, headed the Federalist Party in 1828
when the United Provinces of the River Plate were trying to
organize into the country that would become Argentina.
   He was governor of Buenos Aires province from 1829 to 1831 and
was asked by the legislature to return in 1835. He ruled with
dictatorial powers until his removal in 1852.
   Defeated by Gen. Justo Jose Urquiza, Rosas sought refuge aboard
an English frigate and fled into exile. He died in 1877 at
Southampton, England, where he was buried. The body was exhumed
Sept. 21 for transfer to Paris and then Buenos Aires.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
