<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1708EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TortoiseQuarantine     09-30 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tortoise Quarantine,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Desert Closure to Protect Tortoise Starts Sunday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An emergency quarantine aimed at protecting
the endangered desert tortoise goes into effect Sunday, closing 59
square miles of the Mojave Desert to off-road enthusiasts, hikers
and grazing sheep.
   ``We're losing about 50 percent of the adult tortoises a year
out there right now,'' said Lee Delaney, head of the federal Bureau
of Land Management's area office in Ridgecrest. ``If that
continues, it would be a few short years before we don't have a
tortoise population.''
   BLM workers and volunteers were out Saturday ringing the area
with signs to notify the public of the one-year quarantine, Delaney
said Friday.
   A number of factors are preying on the tortoise, which was
designated an endangered species in August by the U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service. The quarantine will help researchers determine
how and if the problems can be alleviated, Delaney said.
   A respiratory disease is blamed for half of the tortoise deaths,
and more than half of the remaining adult population is showing
signs of the illness, Delaney said. It is hoped the closure will
prevent the disease from spreading.
   The endangered species designation for the tortoise affects
desert areas in Nevada and Utah as well as California.
   In Nevada, where the tortoise is the official state reptile, the
designation is wreaking havoc on the construction boom in Las Vegas.
   The city and several other parties have sued in federal court in
Washington, D.C., claiming restrictions on building should be
confined only to areas where the respiratory disease is a problem.
   Delaney said stress caused by noisy and intrusive all-terrain
vehicles also is believed to be taking a toll on the animals, and
vandals have been shooting them in large numbers.
   The tortoises also are suffering from poor nutrition because of
drought conditions that have reduced vegetation and made drinking
water scarce.
   Predatory ravens also have been picking off newborn tortoises,
Delaney said.
   ``You just wonder if the poor old tortoise isn't on his way out
and there isn't anything we can do about it,'' he mused.
   But he and Jim St. Amant, senior co-chairman of the nonprofit
Desert Tortoise Council, say the preservation effort is worthwhile.
   ``Once they're gone, we don't get a second chance,'' said St.
Amant, also a biologist with the state Department of Fish and Game.
   He noted that the tortoise's welfare is considered an indication
of the quality of the desert habitat, and losses of the reptile
could indicate other species are at risk.
   The tortoise population has dropped sharply since the 1970s,
when the density was estimated at about 250 breeding tortoises per
square mile.
   ``In some areas we're down to about 70 per square mile,''
Delaney said.
   The quarantine area is north of Mojave, a desert city 70 miles
north of Los Angeles. Bordered on the northwest by Koehn Lake, the
area includes a 28-square-mile desert tortoise preserve.
   People caught in the area will be cited for trespassing,
officials have said, and fines will vary depending on several
factors.
   Sheep will be barred from the area in an effort to help increase
vegetation and preserve the topsoil.
   Pilot projects also will be tried during the quarantine,
including one irrigation effort possibly involving pipelines run
from wells on private land.
   Delaney said he was surprised by the support the tortoise
preservation effort has garnered, even from off-road vehicle groups
affected by the closure. Members of one group have volunteered to
help post quarantine signs, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
