<FIRST>u i AM-Pope-Runcie     09-30 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-Runcie,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Runcie Calls on Christians to Recognize Pope as Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto ROM2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archbishop Robert Runcie, the head of the Anglican
church who is discussing unification with the Roman Catholic
church, called Saturday for all Christians to accept the pope as a
common leader ``presiding in love.''
   Runcie made his appeal at an evening prayer service midway
through his first official visit to the Vatican. There was no sign
at the service of the anti-papal militant, the Rev. Ian Paisley of
Northern Ireland, who threatened earlier in the day to disrupt
Runcie's four-day trip.
   Pope John Paul II, who attended the service, encouraged efforts
to unify the two churches but said Anglican ordination of women had
``seriously aggravated the differences between us.''
   Anglican leaders have said they expect to achieve unity with
Catholics in the 21st century, but the churches are still divided
over issues ranging from the meaning of the Eucharist to birth
control.
   Addressing a crowd at the 17th-century Church of St. Gregory,
Runcie said there was an urgent need to strengthen and spread
Christianity.
   ``For the universal church, I renew the plea,'' he said. ``Could
not all Christians come to reconsider the kind of primacy the
bishop of Rome (pope) exercised within the early church, a
`presiding in love' for the sake of the unity of the churches in
the diversity of their mission?''
   Runcie, who as archbishop of Canterbury is spiritual head of the
state Church of England and leader of the world's 70 million
Anglicans, did not detail the role he envisioned for the pope.
   However, Anglican leaders do not appear to want the pontiff to
exercise as much authority over their church as he does over his
own 850 million Roman Catholic followers.
   Anglicans, who broke with the Vatican in the 16th century over
the pope's refusal to give King Henry VIII an annulment, are
divided over whether to accept the pope even as a symbolic leader.
   In his address at the prayer service the pope encouraged a
commission created in 1982 to study creating a theological
framework for unity.
   ``But as we meet today, we cannot but acknowledge that events in
recent years have seriously aggravated the differences between us,
making the work of the commission more difficult,'' said the
pontiff.
   John Paul was referring to a decision by some of the Anglican
church's self-governing groups to allow ordination of women as
priests, a practice not permitted in the Catholic church. One such
church, the U.S. Episcopalians, ordained the first Anglican woman
bishop this year in Boston.
   Earlier in the day, Runcie held his second set of talks with
John Paul. Runcie's secretary for ecumenical affairs, the Rev.
Canon Christopher Hill, characterized the talks as ``extremely
warm, very frank.''
   Also Saturday, Paisley, who heads the anti-Catholic Free
Presbyterian Church in Northern Ireland, delivered a written
protest about Runcie's trip to Runcie's press secretary, Eve
Keatley.
   The letter accused Runcie of ``high treason'' for recent remarks
on the pope's leadership.
   Paisley told journalists he hoped to ``spoil the party'' but
refused to say what he would do.
</TEXT>
