<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2dLdLd-Writethru a0569 09-30 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2d Ld Ld-Writethru, a0569,0708</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jews Observe New Year, Politicians Hopeful on Resolution with Arabs</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS 9th graf bgng: Egyptian President Hosni.... Israel
radio corrects report that Mubarak and Shamir agreed to meet. Corrects
to say they did NOT agree to meet but only to continue their dialogue.
Pickup 10th graf bgng: Mubarak wished...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli politicians on Saturday took an
optimistic view of prospects for peace with Palestinians as Jews
attended prayer services and festive meals for Rosh Hashana, the
Jewish new year.
   But violence continued in the Israeli-occupied territories,
where two Palestinians were reported killed and 12 wounded.
   Troops in the occupied West Bank shot to death a knife-wielding
masked man at a roadblock in the village of Meithalun, military
sources said. Arab reports said the victim was with a group of men
trying to block villagers from leaving for jobs in Israel. Leaders
of the Palestinian uprising had declared a general strike on
Saturday.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, soldiers shot to death
20-year-old Silham Mabruke and wounded six others during clashes in
the area, according to Arab reports. Other Arab reports from the
Gaza Strip said soldiers shot and wounded six Palestinians in
scattered fighting.
   The deaths brought to 577 the number of Palestinians killed by
troops or Jewish settlers in the 21-month-old uprising against
Israeli rule of the occupied lands. Forty Israelis have also been
killed, and 122 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs as
suspected collaborators.
   Israelis observing the Jewish new year 5750 donned holiday garb
and set out on foot for synagogues across the nation. Security was
heavy.
   Rosh Hashana is one of Judaism's holiest days and many
non-observant Jews also attend prayer services on the holiday,
which began Friday at sundown and ends Sunday at sundown.
   ``The peace initiative is alive, fermenting, it is talked about
and argued about,'' Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said in an
interview on Armed Forces radio.
   Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak telephoned Shamir from New York
during a meeting in New York with Foreign Minister Moshe Arens on
Friday and Mubarak and Shamir agreed to continue their dialogue,
Israel radio reported Saturday. Israel radio initially reported
Mubarak and Shamir had agreed to meet but said later that was an
incorrect translation from Hebrew to English and the two leaders
had only agreed to continue their dialogue.
   Mubarak wished Shamir a happy new year in the rare conversation
and said he did not want to see the unity goverment of Israel
divided over a proposal the Egyptian leader put forth to promote
talks between the Jewish state and Palestinians, according to the
radio report.
   But Shamir rejected Mubarak's suggestion that Israel trade
territory for peace and negotiate with the Palestine Liberation
Organization, which Israel considers a terrorist group.
   ``Our peace initiative is based on the idea that the PLO will
not be a determining party, they will not be a factor in the area.
They will be a bothersome party, yes,'' Shamir said.
   Palestinians participating in the uprising in the occupied lands
are demanding an independent state.
   ``To whom should we return these territories? To the
Palestinians? Then you are favoring a Palestinian state,'' Shamir
said.
   Israel's peace initiative calls for Palestinian elections,
followed by interim self-rule and negotiations over the permanent
status of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, home to 1.7 million Arabs.
   Shamir said his Likud bloc and the rival Labor Party of Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Finance Minister Shimon Peres oppose a
Palestinian state.
   Labor does, however, favor some territorial compromise.
   A split developed recently between Likud and Labor, partners in
the coalition government, over Mubarak's invitation to hold talks
in Cairo with a Palestinian delegation including several Arabs
expelled from the occupied lands. Peres accepted the participation
of the deportees but Likud rejected it.
   ``The time has never been riper to start negotiations unless we
want to live always by the sword,'' Peres told Armed Forces radio
Saturday. He said Israel would not accept a PLO delegation as
partners for negotiations but that there was no harm in the PLO
approving the representatives.
</TEXT>
