<FIRST>r a AM-TourismTurndown     09-30 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tourism Turndown,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tourists Spent Less in Massachusetts in Summer of '89</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vacationers kept more of their money to themselves
this summer in Massachusetts, and tourism officials blamed consumer
jitters about the economy for the decline in spending.
   The Massachusetts Office of Travel and Tourism reported that two
out of every three attractions and museums statewide showed a drop
in visitors for an overall decline of 7 percent to 8.3 million
visitors, while hotel occupancy rates, a key indicator of travel
spending, dropped each month from March through July.
   ``Massachusetts had as many summer visitors as last year, but
travelers' concerns about economic conditions were reflected in
reduced spending throughout the state,'' tourism Director Richard
P. Rust said in a prepared statement issued with the recently
released report.
   ``The result was that many tourism businesses had a
disappointing season compared to last year's banner summer,'' he
said
   The dollar value of the declines in tourism was not included in
the report and could not be obtained Saturday.
   Hotels and motels saw fewer overnight guests. April showed the
sharpest decline, down 5.7 percent from last year.
   Attendance at state beaches declined 5.2 percent from 1988, to
5.6 million this year, while there were only 1.6 million visitors
at the state's parks, a 7.6 percent decline from last summer.
   Even sure perennials such as the Boston Tea Party Ship and
Museum suffered. The waterside diversion received 12.9 percent
fewer visitors _ a drop to 69,136 tourists from last year. The
attraction features a small museum and a full-scale replica of one
of the three ships from which rebellious colonists dumped tea into
Boston Harbor to protest the British tea tax.
</TEXT>
