<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-30 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Gets Soaked</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy showers fell on much of the South on Saturday, drenching
parts of Florida with more than 2 inches of rain.
   Mid-afternoon rain and thunderstorms also were reported in
Virginia, South Carolina, Kentucky, Tennessee, Georgia, the Florida
Panhandle, Alabama and Mississippi. Showers also fell in Montana,
Idaho, Nevada, Oregon and Arkansas.
   A flash flood watch was posted through the night over northern
Georgia, the eastern half of Tennessee, the western half of North
Carolina, the southern half of West Virginia, and over much of the
western half of Virginia.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included more than 2 inches at Milton, Fla., more than 1 inch at
Meridian, Miss., and more than 1 inch at Nashville, Tenn., and
Pensacola, Fla.
   Winds were strong and gusty east of a cold front, which reached
from north central Montana across northwest Utah to central
California by late morning. Winds gusted to 38 mph at Cedar City,
Utah, and 40 mph at Salt Lake City, Utah, during the morning.
   Early afternoon temperatures were in the 50s and 60s over New
England; in the 60s and 70s from the Great Lakes across the Ohio
Valley and south through the central Gulf of Mexico Coast; in the
80s over southern Georgia and much of Florida; in the 70s over much
of the Mississippi Valley and in the 80s across a large portion of
the Plains. Temperatures throughout the intermountain region and
the Pacific Coast were in the 50s and 60s, and highs were in the
90s in the desert Southwest.
   Rapid City, S.D., reached 93 degrees on Saturday, which tied its
high temperature record for Sept. 30, set in 1967.
   The low temperature for the lower 48 states Saturday morning was
26 degrees at Canaan, Vt. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m.
EDT ranged from 50 degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 96 degrees at
Needles, Calif., and Yuma, Ariz.
</TEXT>
