<FIRST>u a AM-RoughLanding     09-30 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rough Landing,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Airlines Jet Blows Eight Tires In Rough Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Airlines jet from Osaka, Japan,
blew eight of its 18 tires when it landed Saturday, but none of the
more than 300 people on board was injured, officials said.
   There was no warning before the tires, all on the right side of
the Boeing 747 jet, blew about 10:30 a.m. at San Francisco
International Airport, said United spokeswoman Deborah Jones at the
airline's headquarters in Chicago.
   The pilot of United Flight 810 did not lose control but was
unable to get the jet all the way off a taxiway, closing the runway
until shortly after 1 p.m., said airport spokesman Ron Wilson.
   The passengers were then taken by bus from the plane to the
terminal, he said.
   Wilson said 350 people were on board but Jones said there were
307, including 289 passengers and a crew of 18.
   The jet has eight tires on each side and two in front.
   ``It's not uncommon to have a tire blow, or two,'' Wilson said.
``But it's unusual to have eight go.''
   The plane was taken to United's maintenance base at the airport
for repair of minor damage, Jones said.
</TEXT>
