<HEAD>Blue Jays Defeat Orioles to Clinch American League East</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Toronto Blue Jays captured the American
League East title Saturday when they rallied with three runs in the
eighth inning to beat the Baltimore Orioles, 4-3.
   The Blue Jays ended their September duel with the Orioles,
winning for the second straight day with an eighth-inning comeback.
Mookie Wilson and Fred McGriff tied the score with run-scoring
singles before George Bell hit a sacrifice fly.
   The Orioles' hopes of becoming the first team to go from worst
to first in one season ended in the din of 49,553 screaming fans at
the SkyDome. Baltimore made the fourth-greatest single-season
improvement in history, but it wasn't enough.
   Toronto won its second division championship in five seasons and
will open the playoffs Tuesday night in Oakland.
   Starter Dave Johnson took a two-hitter and 3-1 lead into the
eighth, but left after a leadoff walk to Nelson Liriano. Kevin
Hickey walked Manny Lee and Mark Williamson, 10-5, relieved. Lloyd
Moseby sacrificed and then the Blue Jays' bats took over.
   Frank Wills, 3-1, pitched four scoreless innings and Tom Henke
got his 20th save with a perfect ninth.
