<DOCNO> AP890930-0115 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Walker     09-30 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Walker,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dean of Washington National Cathedral Dies of Heart Failure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Thomas Walker, dean of the Washington
National Cathedral and the city's first black bishop, died of heart
failure Saturday, the Episcopal Diocese of Washington said. He was
64.
   Walker had undergone triple bypass surgery at Georgetown
University Hospital on Friday.
   Walker was vice president of the national House of Bishops of
the Episcopal Church.
   An ardent spokesman for racial conciliation, he supported the
installation of women clergy members in the church.
   Walker joined the Episcopal Church in 1947 and came to
Washington in 1966 to work in a program aimed at the city's poorest
neighborhoods.
   The diocese said Rev. Ronald Haines, the suffragan bishop, would
conduct diocesan affairs until a new diocesan bishop is chosen. A
spokesman said a convention would be scheduled in coming months to
choose a new bishop.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
