<FIRST>u a AM-CocaineSeizure 1stLd-Writethru a0586 09-30 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Seizure, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0586,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three More Arrests Reported; Workers At Complex Were Suspicious</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Six men...' with 2 to CLARIFY that all six were
arrested Friday, but not at the same time. Picks up 7th graf, `The source...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents made three more arrests in the
world's largest cocaine seizure, bringing to six the number held in
connection with the 20 tons found in a suburban warehouse, an
official said Saturday.
   Workers and business owners in the warehouse complex on an
upscale, tree-lined street said they were suspicious about the
establishment, called Adriana's Pottery Warehouse. Adriana's
prosperous-looking operators claimed to be in the velvet painting
business.
   But when authorities acting on a tip broke into the warehouse by
knocking apart a $6 padlock, they found 20 tons of cocaine, the
largest seizure in the world by a law enforcement agency.
   Its estimated value was between $2 billion and $20 billion,
depending on its final form for sale on the street.
   Three Southern California men were arrested Friday morning in
connection with the case. The other three, all from Los Angeles,
were arrested later Friday in their rooms at the Flamingo Hilton in
Las Vegas.
   A U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency source who requested anonymity
identified the men arrested in Las Vegas as Carlos Tapia Ponce, 68,
his son Hector Eduardo Tapia Ponce, 34, and Hector Tapia, 66, the
brother of Carlos.
   The source said Carlos Tapia Ponce is a former Mexican customs
inspector who had worked in Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, for 15 years.
   The three were arrested for investigation of violation of
federal narcotics laws and were booked into the Clark County
Detention Center. Arraignment was set for Monday in U.S. District
Court in Las Vegas.
   The Thursday night raid, 25 miles northwest of downtown near the
San Gabriel Mountain foothills, also yielded extensive records and
at least $10 million in cash, bundled and stuffed in dozens of
boxes.
   ``It didn't seem like a good business,'' said David Barron, the
owner of a construction company that worked out of a warehouse next
door. ``They said they were dealing in paintings _ velvet
paintings. I didn't see a market for that in California.''
   Nonetheless, there were frequent truck deliveries to Adriana's.
Workers in the complex said they came as often as once a week in
the last six months.
   Employees from Adriana's would go from office to office, asking
people to move their cars to make way for the truck.
   Barron said he noticed Adriana's operators ``seemed to be making
an awful lot of money. They were too well-dressed to operate a
warehouse business.''
   Adriana's workers recently spread the word that the deliveries
might start coming twice a week. Barron said some business
operators discussed legal action, or complaining to the police.
   The 20-ton cache was apparently bound for markets across the
United States, but authorities said it already had traveled about
3,500 miles along a route known among law enforcement officials as
``the Trampoline.''
   ``The cocaine is moved from Colombia to Mexico and bounced up
into the United States,'' said Mike Holm, a DEA assistant special
agent in Los Angeles.
   The seizure easily topped the previous U.S. record of about
8,700 pounds recorded in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., in 1987, and
surpassed the world record, a 12-ton seizure in Colombia.
</TEXT>
