<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees-EastBloc     09-30 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-East Bloc,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement To Let East Germans Go Reflects New East Bloc</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The historic international
agreement to allow thousands of East Germans in Czechoslovakia and
Poland to go West underscores the deep political changes at work in
the Soviet bloc.
   In just one eventful night, hard-line Czechoslovakia and
reform-minded Poland have taken their places on the widening route
of East German refugees heading to West Germany.
   Goaded into changes and reforms by Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, the Warsaw Pact nations are taking a new approach to old
problems.
   In years past, East German refugees in Warsaw and Prague would
have had little hope of a successful exit. An escape from East
Germany often involved a desperate swim, a daring leap, a frenzied
dash, or a heart-stopping flight in a homemade glider across the
border.
   The scene was completely different this weekend. West German
television showed Czechoslovak police standing by idly Saturday
afternoon as refugees carried their few belongings in sacks to the
West German Embassy to prepare for the westward journey.
   Hungary, whose Communist leadership has called for multi-party
elections, first opened the floodgates on Sept. 11 by removing
border fences with Austria. That action launched an exodus that
sent nearly 24,000 East German refugees to West Germany and left
the hard-line Communist leadership in East Germany furious.
   Emboldened by Hungary's action, East German refugees gathered at
West German embassies in Warsaw and Prague, where their numbers
swelled to about 4,100. They dug in their heels waiting for
permission to emigrate.
   The unusual agreement Saturday came after weeks of diplomatic
maneuvering, including a round of talks that just ended in New York
during the U.N. General Assembly session, according to West German
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher. He called it ``the most
moving hour of my political work.''
   Genscher stressed the roles of the West German and East German
governments, tactfully leaving out mention of Czechoslovakia and
Poland.
   The issue was sensitive in both countries. Czechoslovakia had
pledged earlier to prevent the East Germans from going to the West.
Despite its reforms and the advent of a government led by a
non-Communist, Poland had balked at agreeing to the refugees'
demands for fear of angering East Germany, a Warsaw Pact ally.
   On Saturday, East Germany said it had agreed to the transfer for
``humanitarian reasons'' and had consulted with both Czechoslovakia
and Poland.
   The official East German news agency ADN wrote of 600 East
Germans in Bonn's embassy in Warsaw being ``expelled.'' ADN also
pointed out that East German trains would take the refugees across
East German territory before they would go on to West Germany.
   The route, a face-saving measure, permitted East Germany to say
that it had allowed the emigrees to go to West Germany from its
territory _ not from Czechoslovakia and Poland.
   Still unknown is what will happen to other East Germans who try
in the future to escape to the West by way of Warsaw and Prague.
East Germany said it expects West Germany to resume ``normal,
international customs'' at its embassies after the transfer.
   Another unanswered question is the amount of pressure West
Germany placed on East Germany to let the refugees go.
   The West Germans appeared to be playing hardball in New York
last week when Genscher skipped the usual niceties at a
face-to-face encounter with his East German counterpart, Oskar
Fischer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
