<FIRST>r a AM-SexAssaultContempt     09-30 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sex Assault Contempt,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Orders Release of Girl Jailed For Not Testifying Against Father</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appellate court has ordered the release
of a 14-year-old girl who was being held for contempt of court
after she refused to testify against her father in a sex abuse case.
   A three-judge panel of the appellate division of Superior Court
ordered the girl's release Friday after her lawyers argued that the
trial judge should have conducted a hearing on whether she was able
to testify when she refused.
   The panel set aside the order of Superior Court Judge David G.
Lucas, who sentenced the girl to serve 60 days at the Somerset
County youth shelter, said George N. Rover, a lawyer for the girl.
   Lucas imposed the sentence Thursday after the girl refused four
times in court to testify against her father at his trial on
charges of sexually abusing her.
   ``You have acted intentionally and you have acted with purpose
to defeat the functions of this court,'' Lucas told the girl after
she refused a fourth time to be sworn in as a witness.
   The girl has repeatedly recanted the allegations.
   The appellate court also ordered a hearing to determine if the
girl is competent to testify, Rover said. He said the girl would
live with her grandparents in Somerset County.
   The father is charged with two counts of aggravated sexual
assault and one count each of sexual assault and endangering the
welfare of a child. He is free on $25,000 bond.
   Timothy Van Hise, the assistant prosecutor trying the case, told
jurors during opening arguments Thursday that authorities learned
about the case in December 1987, after the girl told friends about
the alleged abuse. Van Hise said the father was arrested that day
and confessed to police.
   ``Her desire to stay with her father is not as important as his
egregious criminal conduct,'' Van Hise said. ``You don't press or
not press criminal charges because of the will of family members.''
   ``I have no quarrel with what Judge Lucas did. I think he was
compelled to take the action he took,'' Van Hise said.
</TEXT>
