<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia     09-30 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demobilize Anti-Guerrilla Police Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 former members of a
notorious anti-guerrilla police unit were demobilized Saturday at
their closed base in northern Namibia, the South-West African
Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   Journalists were not permitted into the base at Oshakati where
an estimated 1,150 black and white officers of Koevoet _ which
means crowbar in the Afrikaans language _ marched and were counted
by members of a U.N. mission. The U.N. force is monitoring the
process leading to independence elections for South-West Africa,
now a territory administered by South Africa. The territory also is
known as Namibia.
   The South African Press Association said the former Koevoet
troopers had turned in their uniforms and weapons earlier.
   They had been confined to the Oshakati base since last month,
receiving retraining in ordinary police duties, but they were
allowed to go to their homes at night.
   Since April, when the United Nations began monitoring the
transition to independence, U.N. observers have been calling for
removal of members of the Koevoet unit from the police force.
   Many Koevoet troopers were accused of atrocities during the
23-year bush war between South Africa and the South-West African
People's Organization. SWAPO supporters in northern Namibia claimed
Koevoet members continued to harass and intimidate civilians after
a cease-fire went into effect in April.
   The United Nations, which is responsible for assuring that the
Nov. 7-11 elections are free and fair, adopted a resolution on Aug.
29 calling for the complete demobilization of Koevoet.
   Louis Pienaar, South African administrator of the territory,
disbanded Koevoet as a formal unit and confined them to base. He
suggested they be allowed to remain in the police force until they
were retrained, but his spokesman, Gerhard Roux, said the United
Nations rejected the proposal.
   Roux said Friday that Pienaar was concerned that if the former
Koevoet troopers were responsibile for illegal behavior as
policemen ``now they will be spread out around the country with no
one to control them.''
   Martti Ahtisaari, the U.N. special representative for Namibia,
said in July that 80 percent of the Koevoet members could not write
out a police report and were therefore unfit for normal police
duties. ``Their skills must lie elsewhere,'' he said.
   In another development, SWAPO President Sam Nujoma called on the
United Nations Saturday to take further steps to stop the
``emerging culture of violence'' in the territory. He spoke at the
funeral of Anton Lubowski, the organization's only white executive
member who was assassinated three weeks ago.
   Nujoma, who returned to Namibia recently after some 30 years in
exile, said the failure of police to formally charge anyone with
Lubowski's murder ``smacks of a cover-up.'' Police say they have
arrested an Irishman named Donald Acheson for questioning but no
charges have been filed.
   Lubowski's body was cremated at a private service a week ago.
About 500 people attended the funeral service Saturday at the
Katatura Lutheran Church in a black township near Windhoek, the
capital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
