<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--TransplantBirth     09-30 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Transplant Birth,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two-Time Liver Transplant Patient Has Baby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who underwent two liver transplant
operations while she was pregnant has given birth to a boy, Johns
Hopkins Hospital officials said.
   Martha Maynor, 21, gave birth Friday to Matthew James Maynor by
Caesarian section. Both were in good condition on Saturday, said
hospital spokeswoman Debbie Bangledorf.
   Matthew, 10 weeks premature, weighed 2 pounds, 10 ounces.
   Ms. Maynor was about 22 weeks pregnant when she had the first
liver transplant July 27. A second liver was transplanted three
days later when the first failed. Ms. Maynor's own liver was
destroyed by the Hepatitus B virus.
   Doctors said they had no way of knowing how the fetus would
respond to the anti-rejection drugs his mother was taking.
   Hospital officials said the baby was delivered after tests
indicated the fetus had stopped growing and complications were
likely if the pregnancy continued.
</TEXT>
