<FIRST>r a AM-ArtilleryAccident 1stLd-Writethru a0600 09-30 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Artillery Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0600,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Remembered at Fort Sill Ceremony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Edits throughout to fix typos. No pick up.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SILL, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wounded soldiers, some wearing hospital
attire, were among the 1,500 people who gathered Saturday to mourn
the loss of three comrades killed in an artillery accident.
   Three pairs of boots, three helmets and three upside-down M-16s
with bayonets stood in front of the platform where three Fort Sill
privates gave eulogies for the soldiers.
   ``The emptiness of death is symbolized by the empty boots and
the empty helmets,'' said post spokesman Lt. Col. John Dobbs. ``The
upside down rifle signifies that a comrade-in-arms has fallen.''
   Pvts. 1 Jimmy McCain, 21, of Troy, Ala., and Edward Zastrow, 18,
of Lester Prairie, Minn., and Spec. Thomas Boyle of Ventura,
Calif., were killed Wednesday when an artillery round went nearly a
half-mile off course and exploded near the troops standing in
formation.
   Twenty-four soldiers were wounded. Some of the wounded were
released from the hospital to attend the memorial Saturday, Dobbs
said.
   The memorial, which lasted about 25 minutes, was held outdoors
among the buildings where the fallen soldiers of the A Battery, 2nd
Battalion, 80th Field Artillery, lived, ate and trained, Dobbs said.
   Four chaplains participated in the service, giving the
invocation, reading scriptures, leading a prayer and providing
words of comfort, Dobbs said.
   Battery commander Capt. Mark Wood also spoke.
   ``As we struggle to cope with this tragedy, we can take solace
in our belief that these three fallen soldiers were selfless,
decent men who must sure have found a special place by our just
Lord's side,'' Wood said.
   Seventeen soldiers remained in the hospital Saturday, Dobbs said.
</TEXT>
