<FIRST>r a AM-JetlinerBaby     09-30 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jetliner Baby,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pregnancy Delays Jail Term For Mother Who Gave Birth On Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who gave birth in an
airplane bathroom and stuffed the infant in a wastebasket won't go
to jail until December because she is expecting another baby soon,
officials said.
   Christina LoCasto of New York City was to begin a six-month jail
term Oct. 14, but a San Mateo County Superior Court judge decided
Friday that her sentence should begin after the birth of her fourth
child, which is due in mid-October.
   LoCasto, 25, pleaded no contest in May to a charge of felony
child endangerment in a plea bargain. She could have been sentenced
to six years in prison if she had been tried and convicted.
   The mother of two other children, LoCasto gave birth in the
bathroom of a United Airlines flight between Newark, N.J., and San
Francisco. The baby was found under the sink shortly after the
airplane landed at San Francisco International Airport on July 13,
1988.
   LoCasto told caseworkers last year she was afraid to tell her
husband about her third pregnancy because they were having marital
problems.
   A juvenile court judge awarded temporary custody of the baby,
named Alyssa, to her paternal grandparents. Another hearing on her
custody will be held Oct. 25.
</TEXT>
