<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 2243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MormonConference     09-30 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mormon Conference,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Apologize For Old Age But Defend Prophetic Callings</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SK3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERN ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mormon Church apostle on Saturday
apologized for the leadership's human frailties, brought on by old
age, but issued a call for obedience to church decrees.
   ``We are sorry for our inadequacies, sorry that we are not
better than we are. We see, as you see, the erosion of age as it
limits and enfeebles his leaders before your very eyes,'' said
Elder Boyd K. Packer, 65.
   The 15 members of the governing First Presidency and Twelve
Apostles of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints average
69 years of age and serve under a system of apostolic succession
until death.
   Packer and other members of the Quorum of the Mormon Church
convened the faith's 159th Semiannual General Conference with calls
for obedience to revelation.
   ``There are those within the church who are disturbed when
changes they propose are not made, or when changes are made with
which they disagree,'' Packer said. ``They point to these changes
as evidence that the leaders are not inspired.''
   Such critics are ``always irritated by the word `obedience' and
always they question revelation. It always has been so,'' Packer
said.
   The remarks seemed aimed to counter criticism from George P.
Lee, a member of the First Quorum of the Seventy and a Navajo, who
was excommunicated a month ago in a dispute over for the doctrinal
role of Indians in the faith.
   Members of the church's hierarchy also condemned drug use as a
form of murder, reaffirmed that women cannot hold the priesthood
and said the safety of thousands of young missionaries amid
political turmoil abroad is ``a paramount concern.''
   The Mormons' president, Ezra Taft Benson, attended the gathering
in the Tabernacle on Temple Square, but one of his counselors,
Thomas S. Monson, read the 90-year-old church's leader's address.
Benson praised the faith's elderly and counseled their families to
honor them.
   Elder James E. Faust of the Twelve said that while he and his
brethren make no claim to infallibility or perfection, their
responsibility is to receive revelation for the entire 6.7
million-member church.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
