<DOCNO> AP890930-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 2313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ChurchProtest     09-30 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Church Protest,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dissidents Call an End to Protest at Polish Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident parishoners of a
predominantly Polish Roman Catholic church say they have ended
their 41-week demonstration calling for the resignation of their
pastor.
   ``We're frustrated and it's time to stop,'' said Brian Syc, a
spokesman for the group.
   The protesters were calling for removal of the Rev. John Bambol,
pastor at St. Michael the Archangel Church. The group says it will
continue to withhold financial support from the parish and attend
other churches until its demands are met.
   ``This is not a happy occasion,'' Vincent Knapczyk, another
spokesman, said Friday. ``We accomplished something. We showed that
people could unite if they think something is important.'' For 10
months, demonstrators had gathered on the street outside the church
to sing and protest.
   When told about the end of the protest, Bambol said he didn't
care what the group decided to do, calling its demands senseless.
   ``I didn't pay attention to those people. They disturbed and
harassed people in the church. It will be a relief for the people
in church,'' Bambol said.
   The schism that divided the parish began in the summer of 1988
and exploded in December when Bambol called for the opening of the
church to non-Poles. His recommendation sparked an angry reaction
from some parishoners who said the proposal threatened the Polish
character of the parish.
   Shortly after the protests began, the Rev. Roman Palaszewski,
who was popular with many recent Polish immigrants, was ordered to
leave the parish by the Franciscan Order. Some parishioners blamed
Bambol for the priest's transfer and occupied the church for a week.
   The sit-in ended Feb. 18, when church authorities summoned
police to evict the demonstrators. The church then closed for three
Sundays.
   Palaszewski eventually was suspended by his superiors for not
returning to Poland as he was ordered to do. The priest went into
hiding and became the rallying point for the protesters.
   Since then, Palaszewski has traveled to the Vatican to plead to
stay in the United States. He remains in Poland awaiting a decision
on his request, Syc said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
