<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0581 09-30 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0581,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans in Poland Start Trip West</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates number of refugees to 809, train leaves Warsaw, identifies
both West German officials travelling with refugees grafs 1-6. Pickup 6th
graf pvs: The diplomat told... </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With cheers and tears, more than 800 East
German refugees in Warsaw heard a West German diplomat announce
Saturday night they could take a train to the West and ``go
tomorrow to the Octoberfest in Munich.''
   The announcement followed a highly unusual East-West accord that
also allows about 3,500 East Germans in Czechoslovakia to go to
West Germany. The latest East German refugees will be following
23,000 countrymen who emigrated this month through Hungary after
earlier diplomatic talks.
   The East Germans in Warsaw assembled late Saturday at the West
German Embassy to prepare for their trip. The embassy had been
closed for more than a week to prevent additional East Germans from
taking refuge there.
   Applause interrupted the West German diplomat at virtually every
sentence as he told the East Germans they would leave Warsaw's
Eastern Station by train at about 2:50 a.m. Sunday (9:50 p.m. EDT
Saturday) en route to their new lives in West Germany.
   And at 2:50 a.m. the train pulled out with 809 refugees aboard
for the journey to the West German border city of Helmstedt. The
trip was expected to take about 10 hours.
   The train would stop only once in East Germany, where the
refugees would receive their emigration papers, the diplomat said.
They were escorted by West German State Secretary Jurgen Sudhoff
and Franz Bertle, head of the West German mission in East Germany.
   The diplomat told the crowd of jubilant refugees they would
arrive in time to attend the traditional fall festival, the
Octoberfest, in Munich.
   Tears streamed down the refugees' faces as they hugged each
other and left the crowded embassy hall to pack their belongings.
   ``I am happy, I am happy'' one young man said, speaking through
the bars of the compound gates.
   The refugees arranged their overstuffed luggage, backpacks and
teddy bears. They bundled up their children against the chill, wet
evening and finished assembling the few possessions they would be
taking with them.
   Along the tree-lined streets a dozen buses from the state
tourism agency were parked to take the refugees to the train
station.
   Earlier in the evening, those refugees who had been allowed to
live near the embassy in a residential section of Warsaw were
escorted to the compound, where others had waited out the
diplomatic talks. Some had been there for more than a month.
   Poland, where Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki has headed the
East bloc's only non-communist government since Sept. 12, had taken
a cautious approach to the delicate diplomatic problem.
   While the reform-oriented government wanted to see the East
Germans given passage to the West, Poland was sensitive to
straining relations with East Germany, its neighbor and Warsaw Pact
ally. When he took office, Mazowiecki pledged to respect Warsaw
Pact commitments.
   On Thursday, after negotiations with East German envoy Wolfgang
Vogel, about 50 refugees in Poland accepted their government's
offer to emigrate legally if they returned home.
   On Saturday, East Germany said it had agreed to let the refugees
in Poland and Czechoslovakia go to the West and that Poland had
been consulted in the decision.
   During their stay, the refugees in Poland ate food bought for
them at hotels and markets around Warsaw. Trucks from West Germany
brought in bunk beds and other supplies, and humanitarian agencies
made donations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
