<FILEID>AP-NR-09-30-89 2321EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-EarhartExpedition     09-30 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earhart Expedition,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battery, Metal Not from Earhart's Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WALTON BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coral-encrusted battery and two
pieces of aluminum found off a South Pacific atoll did not come
from an aircraft, say members of a team searching for the wreckage
of Amelia Earhart's plane.
   Divers found the items Monday, leading to speculation they may
have come from Earhart's plane, which vanished 52 years ago with
her and navigator Fred Noonan aboard during an attempt to fly
around the world.
   The searchers reported Friday they had concluded the pieces did
not come from an aircraft, said spokesmen Tom Gannon, in telephone
interviews from Suva, Fiji.
   ``It's back to square one, I guess,'' said Gannon, a retired Air
Force navigator from this florida panhandle city.
   Gannon and Tom Willi, a retired Navy pilot, are at a
communications post in Fiji linked with 28 members of the
expedition on Nikumaroro Island, about 900 miles to the north in
the Phoenix Islands group.
   Willi and Gannon persuaded the International Group for Historic
Aircraft Recovery to search for Earhart's plane after they used
1930s navigational techniques to plot a course indicating the plane
may have gone down on or near Nikumaroro, a small, jungle atoll.
   Expedition leader Rick Gillespie contacted Willi on Friday with
a terse message saying that the items found were no longer
considered aircraft-related.
   Gillespie said he believed the battery was discarded by natives
who settled on the island in 1938, a year after the plane vanished.
The atoll was abandoned in the 1950s after the islanders'
British-sponsored attempt to develop a coconut palm industry failed.
   The searchers concluded that a 7-foot-long aluminum pipe was too
big and heavy to have come from an aircraft. And it seemed unlikely
that a solid, egg-shaped chunk of aluminum found was an airplane's
brake drum, as Gillespie first theorized, Willi said.
   Gillespie will continue the expedition and return with the
search vessel to Fiji on Oct. 10, Gannon said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
